Naught but pure Juliet and Romeo.
Say, who acts best? Drusus or Roscio,
Now I have him, that ne'er of ought did speak
But when of plays or Players he did treat.
H'ath made a common-place book out of plays,
And speaks in print: […] speaks he not movingly,
From out some new pathetic Tragedy?
He writes, he rails, he jests, he courts what not,
And all from out his huge long scraped stock
Of well-penn'd plays.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Borachio

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Beatrice:] [...] Therefore I will [...] lead his apes into hell.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
A hall, a hall,
Room for the Spheres, the Orbs celestial
Will dance Kemp's Jig. They'll revel with neat jumps
A worthy Poet hath put on their Pumps.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
So Labeo did complain his love was stone,
Obdurate, flinty, so relentless none:
 Yet Lynceus knows, that in the end of this,
He wrought as strange a metamorphosis.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Balurdo (sings):] Do me right,
And dub me knight,
Balurdo.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Galeatzo:] Good faith, I'll accept of the coxcomb, so you will not refuse the bauble.
[Mellida:] Nay, good sweet, keep them both; I am enamoured of neither.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Calphurnia:] When beggars die there are no comets seen;
 The heavens themselves blaze forth the death of princes.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Antony:] Over thy wounds now do I prophesy
(Which like dumb mouths do ope their ruby lips
To beg the voice and utterance of my tongue) [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Pistol:] Trail'st thou the puissant pike?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Mellida:] Nothing sweet Rossaline, but the air's sharp.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Andrugio:] Myself, myself will dare all opposites [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Lucio:] I saw no sun today.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Andrugio:] 'Tis a good boy, & by my truth, well sung.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Alberto:] For woods, trees, sea, or rocky Apennine,
Is not so ruthless as my Rossaline.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Agripyna:] [...] My mouth is like a Furnace, and dry heat
Drinks up my blood.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Alberto:] [...] idiot, go by, go by; off this world's stage!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Cazzo:] [...] to view our masters pluck their plumes and drop their feathers, for fear of being men of mark.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Bellamira:] <span class="quote">Poison my face! oh most inhumane wretch! Revenge more vile, then to abridge my life.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Andrugio:] O, a fair cause stands firm and will abide;
Legions of Angels fight upon her side.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Antonio:] [...] Rolled up in gloomy clouds as black as air
Through which the rusty coach of Night is drawn.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Andrugio:] [...] Who is not blown up with the flattering puffs
Of spongy sycophants [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Balurdo:] [...] stewed broth of plums (boy keel your mouth, it runs over - and the word shall be: Hold my dish, whilst I spill my pottage.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Andrugio:] Andrugio lives, and a fair cause of arms,
Why that's an army all invincible.
He who hath that, hath a battalion
Royal, armour of proof, huge troops of barbed steeds,
Main squares of pikes, millions of arquebus.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] The dram of evil
Doth all the noble substance of a doubt
To his own scandal.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] But, in the verity of extolment [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Horatio:] Look, my lord, it comes.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] If it assume my noble father's person [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] as I pronounced it to you, trippingly on the tongue; but if you mouth it, as many of our players do, I had as lief the town-crier spoke my lines.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] Be thou a spirit of health or goblin damned,
Bring with thee airs from heaven or blasts from hell,
Be thy intents wicked or charitable,
Thou com'st in such a questionable shape [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] That thou, dead corse, again in complete steel [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [King:] [...] This grave shall have a living monument.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ophelia:] [...] Like sweet bells jangled, out of tune and harsh [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Polonius:] [...] the desk or table-book [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] Still am I called. Unhand me, gentlemen.
By heaven, I'll make a ghost of him that lets me!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Gertrude:] But, look, where sadly the poor wretch comes reading.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] Suit the action to the word, the word to the action [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Antonio:] [...] A blazing comet shot his threat'ning train [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] you are a fishmonger.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Polonius:] Ay, springes to catch woodcocks.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] Speak. I am bound to hear.
[Ghost:] So art thou to revenge, when thou shalt hear.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Claudius:] [...] In equal scale weighing delight and dole [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] whose end, both at the first and now, was and is to hold, as 'twere, the mirror up to nature, to show virtue her own feature, scorn her own image [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] As e'er my conversation coped withal.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] Who calls me "villain"? breaks my pate across? Plucks off my beard and blows it in my face?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] A little more than kin, and less than kind.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ghost:] I am thy father's spirit [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Gertrude:] [...] Thou know'st 'tis common; all that lives must die,
Passing through nature to eternity.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] and I will wear him
In my heart's core, ay, in my heart of heart,
As I do thee.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Claudius:] [...] in obstinate condolement [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] Do not itself unkennel in one speech [...]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Claudius:] [...] Fie, 'tis a fault to heaven,
A fault against the dead, a fault to nature [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ghost:] [...] To tell the secrets of my prison house [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Horatio:] [...] And flights of angels sing thee to thy rest!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] It is a damnèd ghost that we have seen [...]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ghost:] [...] Make thy two eyes, like stars, start from their spheres [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] That's a fair thought to lie between maids' legs.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] hobby-horse, whose epitaph is “For oh, for oh, the hobby-horse is forgot.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ghost:] [...] Like quills upon the fearful porpentine.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Horatio:] [...] Armed at point exactly, cap-à-pie [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ophelia:] What means this, my lord?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] Marry, this is miching mallecho; it means mischief.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] Haste me to know 't, that I, with wings as swift
As meditation or the thoughts of love,
May sweep to my revenge.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Pandulpho:] Methinks I hear a humming murmur creep from out his jellied wounds. Look on those lips [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Player King:] My operant powers their functions leave to do.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] Not where he eats, but where he is eaten. A certain convocation of politic worms are e’en at him. Your worm is your only emperor for diet. We fat all creatures else to fat us, and we fat ourselves for maggots.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] When honor's at the stake.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] O, my prophetic soul!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[First Clown (sings):] A pick-axe, and a spade, a spade,
For and a shrouding sheet:
O, a pit of clay for to be made
For such a guest is meet.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] gives me the lie i' th' throat [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ghost:] Ay, that incestuous, that adulterate beast [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King:] [...] O, my offense is rank, it smells to heaven;
It hath the primal eldest curse upon 't,
A brother's murder.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] Let it work,
For 'tis the sport to have the enginer
Hoist with his own petard; and 't shall go hard
But I will delve one yard below their mines
And blow them at the moon.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ghost:] [...] But virtue, as it never will be moved,
Though lewdness court it in a shape of heaven,
So, lust, though to a radiant angel linked,
Will sate itself in a celestial bed
And prey on garbage.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] I'll take the ghost's word for a thousand pound.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ghost:] [...] Most lazar-like, with vile and loathsome crust [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ghost:] My hour is almost come
When I to sulf'rous and tormenting flames
Must render up myself.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ghost:] Taint not thy mind, nor let thy soul contrive
Against thy mother aught. Leave her to heaven [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Bernardo:] See, it stalks away!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] let not ever
The soul of Nero enter this firm bosom.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ghost:] [...] The glowworm shows the matin to be near [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] Within the book and volume of my brain [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] That one may smile and smile and be a villain [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Marcellus:] Illo, ho, ho, my lord!
[Hamlet:] Hillo, ho, ho, boy!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] For every man hath business and desire [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] I will go pray.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] Art thou there, truepenny?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ghost (beneath):] Swear.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] Hic et ubique? Then we'll shift our ground.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Horatio:] O day and night, but this is wondrous strange.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] There are more things in heaven and earth, Horatio,
Than are dreamt of in your philosophy.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] Tis not alone my inky cloak, good mother,
Nor customary suits of solemn black [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] Or that the Everlasting had not fixed
His canon 'gainst self-slaughter!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Horatio:] [...] In the dead waste and middle of the night [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] Aeneas' tale to Dido

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Laertes:] [...] And, like the kind life-rend'ring pelican,
Repast them with my blood.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Antonio:] Now croaks the toad, & night-crows screech aloud,
Fluttering 'bout casements of departed souls.
Now gapes the graves, and through their yawns let loose
Imprison'd spirits to revisit earth [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] I must be cruel only to be kind.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] Why, then, 'tis none to you, for there is nothing either good or bad but thinking makes it so. To me, it is a prison.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ophelia:] [...] Come, my coach! Good night ladies, good night sweet ladies [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Claudius:] [...] And wants not buzzers to infect his ear [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Laertes:] [...] both the worlds I give to negligence [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] Now might I do it pat, now he is a-praying,
And now I'll do 't. (He draws his sword)
And so he goes to heaven,
And so am I revenged.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] Angels and ministers of grace defend us!

[Hamlet]: [...] Save me, and hover o'er me with your wings,
You heavenly guard! What would your gracious figure?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] 'Sblood, do you think I am easier to be played on than a pipe? Call me what instrument you will, though you can fret me, yet you cannot play upon me.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] The rugged Pyrrhus, like th' Hyrcanian beast [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Jaques:] And one man in his time plays many parts,
his acts being seven ages.At first the infant,
Mewling and puking in the nurse’s arms.
Then the whining schoolboy with his satchel
And shining morning face, creeping like snail
Unwillingly to school. And then the lover,
Sighing like furnace, with a woeful ballad
Made to his mistress’ eyebrow. Then a soldier,
Full of strange oaths and bearded like the pard,
Jealous in honor, sudden and quick in quarrel,
Seeking the bubble reputation
Even in the cannon’s mouth. And then the justice,
In fair round belly with good capon lined,
With eyes severe and beard of formal cut,
Full of wise saws and modern instances;
And so he plays his part. The sixth age shifts
Into the lean and slippered pantaloon
With spectacles on nose and pouch on side,
His youthful hose, well saved, a world too wide
For his shrunk shank, and his big manly voice,
Turning again toward childish treble, pipes
And whistles in his sound. Last scene of all,
That ends this strange eventful history,
Is second childishness and mere oblivion,
Sans teeth, sans eyes, sans taste, sans everything.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Epilogue:] I'll only speak, what I have heard him say;
By (-) 'tis good, and if you lik't, you may.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] O all you host of heaven!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Pandulpho:] [...] thou and I
Will talk as Chorus to this tragedy.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Horatio:] [...] It harrows me with fear and wonder.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
And, like a man to double business bound,
I stand in pause where I shall first begin,
And both neglect.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Horatio:] [...] Together with that fair and warlike form [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Rosalind:] […] Wilt thou love such a woman? What, to make thee an instrument and play false strains upon thee?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Horatio:] [...] Such was the very armor he had on
When he the ambitious Norway combated.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Horatio:] [...] Which he stood seized of, to the conqueror.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Horatio:] A mote it is to trouble the mind's eye.


[Hamlet:] In my mind's eye, Horatio.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Horatio:] [...] And even the like precurse of feared events [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Marcellus:] [...] Some say that ever 'gainst that season comes
Wherein our Savior’s birth is celebrated,
This bird of dawning singeth all night long;
And then, they say, no spirit dare stir abroad,
The nights are wholesome; then no planets strike,
No fairy tales, nor witch hath power to charm,
So hallowed and so gracious is that time.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [King:] [...] With mirth in funeral and with dirge in marriage [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Queen:] [...] Do not forever with thy vailèd lids
Seek for thy noble father in the dust.
Thou knows't 'tis common; all that lives must die,
Passing through nature to eternity.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [King:] [...] That father lost, lost his, and the survivor bound [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [King:] Break not your sleeps for that.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [King:] [...] But the great cannon to the clouds shall tell [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] Now could I drink hot blood
And do such bitter business as the day
Would quake to look on. Soft, now to my mother.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] O, that this too, too sullied flesh would melt,
Thaw, and resolve itself into a dew [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] Fie on 't, ah fie! 'Tis an unweeded garden
That grows to seed. Things rank and gross in nature
Possess it merely.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] Hyperion to a satyr; so loving to my mother
That he might not beteem the winds of heaven
Visit her face too roughly.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] Like Niobe, all tears - why she, even she [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] (O God, a beast that wants discourse of reason
Would have mourned longer!)

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] With such dexterity to incestuous sheets!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] But break, my heart, for I must hold my tongue.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: (There is a love triangle in which the rejected suitor rubs poison in a girl's face; she is restored and able to marry the right man).

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] Thrift, thrift, Horatio. The funeral baked meats
Did coldly furnish forth the marriage tables.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Barnardo:] Tis now struck twelve. Get thee to bed, Francisco.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Rosalind as Ganymede:] Break an hour's promise in love? He that will divide a minute into a thousand parts and break but a part of the thousand part of a minute in the affairs of love, it may be said of him that Cupid hath clapped him o' th' shoulder, but I'll warrant him heart-whole.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] He was a man. Take him for all in all,
I shall not look upon his like again.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Horatio:] [...] Thrice he walked
By their oppressed and fear-surprisèd eyes [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Horatio:] [...] whilst they, distilled
Almost to jelly with the act of fear,
Stand dumb and speak not to him.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] Armed, say you?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Celia:] <span class="quote">He hath bought a pair of cast lips of Diana. /span>A nun of winter's sisterhood kisses not more religiously. The very ice of chastity is in them.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] My father’s spirit in arms! All is not well.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ophelia:] No more but so?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Horatio:] [...] by heaven I charge thee, speak!
[...] Stay! speak! speak! I charge thee, speak!
[...] Speak to me.
[...] Speak to me.
[...] O, speak!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] O, vengeance!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Laertes:] [...] In thews and bulk but, as this temple waxes [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Queen:] [...] The Queen carouses to thy fortune, Hamlet.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] The spirit that I have seen
May be the devil, and the devil hath power
T’ assume a pleasing shape; yea, and perhaps,
Out of my weakness and my melancholy,
As he is very potent with such spirits,
Abuses me to damn me.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Laertes:] [...] And now no soil nor cautel doth besmirch
The virtue of his will [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Laertes:] [...] He may not, as unvalued persons do,
Carve for himself, for on his choice depends
The safety and the health of this whole state.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Laertes:] [...] Unto the voice and yielding of that body [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Laertes:] [...] As he in his particular act and place
May give his saying deed [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Balurdo:] Courage, courage sweet Lady, 'tis sir Gefferey Balurdo bids you courage. Truly I am as nimble as an Elephant about a Lady.
[Panulpho Felice:] Dead?
[Antonio:] Dead.
[Alberto:] Dead?
[Antonio:] Why now the womb of mischief is deliver'd,
Of the prodigious issue of the night.
[Panulpho Felice:] Ha, ha, ha.
[Antonio:] My father dead, my love attained of lust:
Thats a large lye, as vast as spacious hell:
Poor guiltless Lady.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Laertes:] [...] And keep you in the rear of your affection,
Out of the shot and danger of desire.
The chariest maid is prodigal enough
If she unmask her beauty to the moon.
Virtue itself 'scapes not calumnious strokes.
The canker galls the infants of the spring
Too oft before their buttons be disclosed,
And, in the morn and liquid dew of youth,
Contagious blastments are most imminent.
Be wary, then; best safety lies in fear.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ophelia:] [...] Do not, as some ungracious pastors do,
Show me the steep and thorny way to heaven
Whiles, like a puffed and reckless libertine
Himself the primrose path of dalliance treads
And recks not his own rede.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Polonius:] [...] Give thy thoughts no tongue [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Polonius:] [...] Those friends thou hast, and their adoption tried,
Grapple them unto thy soul with hoops of steel [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Polonius:] [...] Take each man's censure, but reserve thy judgment.
Costly thy habit as thy purse can buy,
But not expressed in fancy (rich, not gaudy) [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Touchstone:] I am here with thee and thy goats, as the most capricious poet, honest Ovid, was among the Goths.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] Whether 'tis nobler in the mind to suffer [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ophelia:] 'Tis in my memory locked,
And you yourself shall keep the key of it.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Polonius:] [...] Do not believe his vows, for they are brokers [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] Or to take arms against a sea of troubles [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] And, as he drains his draughts of Rhenish down [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] And, by opposing, end them. To die, to sleep -
No more - and by a sleep to say we end [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] The kettledrum and trumpet thus bray out
The triumph of his pledge.
[Horatio:] Is it a custom?
[Hamlet:] Ay, marry, is 't [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] This heavy-headed revel east and west [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] How absolute the knave is! We must speak by the card, or equivocation will undo us.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] For in that sleep of death what dreams may come
When we have shuffled off this mortal coil,
Must give us pause [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Polonius

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] They clepe us drunkards and with swinish phrase
Soil our addition.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] The pith and marrow of our attribute.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] But he's an arrant knave.

 [Hamlet:] [...] We are arrant knaves [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] So oft it chances in particular men
That for some vicious mole of nature in them,
As in their birth (wherein they are not guilty,
Since nature cannot choose his origin)
[...] Carrying, I say, the stamp of one defect,
Being nature's livery or fortune's star,
His virtues else, be they as pure as grace,
As infinite as man may undergo,
Shall in the general censure take corruption [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Toby:] [...] My very walk should be a jig. I would not so much as make water but in a sink-a-pace.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Here now, put case our Author should, once more,
Swear that his play were good: he doth implore
You would not argue him of arrogance [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Gvy:] Or like a blazing comet, that foretells
The fall of princes.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hieronimo:] [...] And yonder pale faced He-cat there, the Moon,
Doth give consent to that is done in darkness,
And all those Stars that gaze upon her face,
Are agates on her sleeve pins on her train,
And those that should be powerful and divine,
Do sleep in darkness when they most should shine.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Fortunatus:] He can convey her forth her father's gate,
Unto a secret friend of hers;
The way to whom lies by his forest side,
That none but he shall have her to his bride.

[...] I have a secret friend, that dwells from hence [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Guy:] Brother, if I knew where to go to war,
I would not stay in London one hour longer.
[Charles:] An hour! By heaven I would not stay a minute.
[Eustache:] A minute, not a moment. Would you put a moment
Into a thousand parts, the thousandth part,
Would not I linger, might I go to war.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Troilus:] [...] Why keep we her? The Grecians keep our Aunt:
Is she worth keeping? Why she is a Pearl,
Whose price hath launch'd above a thousand Ships [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Malevole:] [...] Do the sword dance [...] and run the wild-goose chase even with Pompey the huge.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Altofronto

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Not mine own fears, nor the prophetic soul
Of the wide world dreaming on things to come,
Can yet the lease of my true love control,
Supposed as forfeit to a confined doom.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Isabella:] [...] Why all the souls that were were forfeit once,
And He that might the vantage best have took
Found out the remedy. How would you be
If He which is the top of judgment should
But judge you as you are? O, think on that,
And mercy then will breathe within your lips
Like man new-made.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ferneze:] Your smiles have been my heaven your frowns my hell,
O pity then; Grace should with beauty dwell.
[Maquerelle:] Reasonable perfect bir-lady.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Pompey:] [...] Then is there here one Master Caper, at the suit of Master Three-pile the mercer, for some four suits of peach-colored satin, which now peaches him a beggar. Then have we here young Dizzy and young Master Deep-vow, and Master Copper-spur and Master Starve-lackey the rapier-and-dagger man, and young Drop-heir that killed lusty Pudding, and Master Forth-light the tilter, and brave Master Shoe-tie the great traveler, and wild Half-can that stabbed Pots, and I think forty more, all great doers in our trade, and are now "for the Lord’s sake."

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Malevole:] [sings] When Arthur first in Court began, - Agamemnon Menelaus - was every any Duke a Cornuto?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Malevole:] Ay, I will come, friendly Damnation, I will come [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Malevole:] Soft rest, sweet Music, amorous Masqueraders, lascivious banquets, sin itself gilt ore [...] impudent custom incited by that great bawd opportunity, thus being prepar'd, clap to her easy ear [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Maquerelle:] promise of matrimony by a young gallant, to bring a virgin Lady into a fool's paradise [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Malevole:] I cannot sleep, my eyes ill neighbouring lids
Will hold no fellowship [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Pompey:] Sir, she came in great with child, and longing, saving your Honor’s reverence, for stewed prunes.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Celso:] I faith my Lord, that beast with many heads
The staggering multitude recoils apace,
Though thorow great mens envy, most men's malice,
Their much intemperate heat hath banished you.
Yet now they find envy and malice near,
Produce faint reformation.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Malevole:] [...] I'll give you a simile; Did you e'er see a well with two buckets, whilst one comes up full to be emptied, another goes down empty to be filled? Such is the state of all humanity [...]. why look you, I may be the son of some Duke; for, believe me, ïntemperate lascivious bastardy makes Nobility doubtful: I have a lusty, daring heart, Mendoza.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Iago:] Wears out his time, much like his master’s ass,
For naught but provender [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Iago:] [...] Put money in thy purse. Follow thou the wars; defeat thy favor with an usurped beard. I say, put money in thy purse.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Freewill:] [...] So could I live in desert most unknown,
Yourself to me enough were Populous [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
As a black veil upon the wings of morn,
Brings forth a day as clear as Venus' face,
Or, a fair Jewel by an Ethiop worn,
Enricheth much the eye, which it doth grace,
Such is her beauty, if it well be told,
Plac'st in a Jetty Chariot set with gold.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Iago:] O, beware, my lord, of jealousy!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Brabantio:] Look to her, Moor, if thou hast eyes to see.
She has deceived her father, and may thee.


[Iago:] She did deceive her father, marrying you [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hipolito:] What's here?
Perhaps this shrewd pate was mine enemy's:
Las! say it were: I need not fear him now:
For all his braves, his contumelious breath,
His frowns (tho dagger-pointed) all his plot,
(Tho 'nere so mischievous) his Italian pills,
His quarrels, and (that common fence) his law, [...]
And must all come to this; fools; wise, all hether,
Must all heads thus at last be laid together: [...]
But here's a fellow; that which he lays on,
Till dooms day, alters not complexion.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Iago:] [...] Not poppy nor mandragora
Nor all the drowsy syrups of the world [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Othello:] I'll tear her all to pieces.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Othello:] [...] And mak'st me call what I intend to do
A murder, which I thought a sacrifice!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Mrs. Mulligrub:] [...] I ha' wit, and can see my good as soon as another, for I have all the thanks, my silly husband, alas, he knows nothing of it, tis I that bear, tis I that must bear a brain for all.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Candido:] No matter, let 'em: when I touch her lip,
I shall not feel his kisses, no, nor miss
Any of her lip; no harm in kissing is.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Mrs. Mulligrub:] [...] nay and I bear not a brain [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Tissefeu:] Then thus, and thus, so Hymen should begin -
Sometimes a falling out proves falling in.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Crispinella:] [...] his discourse is like the long word, Honorificabilitudinitatibus: a great deal Of sound and no sense.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Comolet:] [...] You know besides, that our affections storm,
Rais'd in our blood, no Reason can reform.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Tamyra:] It is not I, but urgent destiny,
That (as great states men for their general end
In politique justice, make poor men offend)
Enforceth my offence to make it just:
What shall weak Dames do, when t'whole work of Nature
Hath a strong finger in each one of us?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Othello

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Iago:] Ha! I like not that.
[Othello:] What dost thou say?
[Iago:] Nothing, my lord: or if - I know not what.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Iago:] Come on, come on! You are pictures out of door, bells in your parlors, wildcats in your kitchens, saints in your injuries, devils being offended, players in your huswifery, and huswives in your beds.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Othello:] I slept the next night well, fed well, was free and merry.
I found not Cassio's kisses on her lips.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Title: The Case is Altered

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Desdemona:] Nobody. I myself. Farewell.
Commend me to my kind lord. O, farewell.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lear:] [...] But yet thou art my flesh, my blood, my daughter,
Or, rather, a disease that's in my flesh,
Which I must needs call mine.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Herod:] [...] Now the Jail deliver me, an intelligencer, be good to me ye Cloisters of bondage, of whence art thou?
[Hercules:] Of Ferrara.
[Herod:] A Ferarees what to me, camest thou in with the Prince Tiberio?
[Hercules:] With the Prince Tiberio , what a that, you will not rayle at me, will you?
[Herod:] Who I? I rail at one of Ferrara, a Ferazees , noe? didst thou ride?
[Hercules:] No.
[Herod:] Hast thou worn socks?
[Hercules:] No.
[Herod:] Then blessed be the most happy gravel betwixt thy toes I do prophesy thy tyrannising itch shall be honourable, and thy right worshipful soul shall appear in full presence; art thou an officer to the Princes.
[Hercules:] I am, what a that?
[Herod:] My cap, what officer?
[Hercules:] Yeoman of his bottles, what to that?
[Herod:] My lip, thy name good yeoman of the bottles?
[Hercules:] Faunus.
[Nymphadoro:] Faunus an old Courtier, I wonder thou art in no better clothes and place Faunus?
[Hercules:] I may be in better place sir, and with them of more regard if this match of our Dukes intermarriage with the heir of Urbin proceed, the Duke of Urbin dying, and our Lord coming in his Lady's right title to your dukedom.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Nymphadoro:] How? the Prince? would he only stood cross to my wishes, he should find me an Italian.
 [Hercules:] How, an Italian
[Herod:] By thy aid an Italian, dear Faunus , thou art now wriggled into the Prince's bosom, and thy sweet hand should Minister that Nectar to him, should make him immortal; Nymphadoro in direct phrase, thou should'st murder the Prince, so revenge thine own wrongs, and be rewarded for that revenge.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hercules:] As for that most precious light of heaven Truth, if time be the father of her, I am sure drunkenness is oftentimes the mother of her, and brings her forth, drunkenness brings all out, for it brings all the drink out of the pot, all the wit out of the pate, and all the money out of the purse.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Herod:] Come Sir, a stool boy, these Court Feasts are to us Servitors Court Fasts, such scrambling, such shift for to eat, and where to eat, here a Squire of low degree hath got the carcass of a Plover, there Pages of the Chamber divide the spoils of a tattered Pheasant, here the Sewer has friended a Country Gentleman with a sweet green goose, and there a young fellow that late has bought his office, has caught a Woodcock by the nose, with cups full ever flowing.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Dondolo:] An other that there is no present time, and that one man to day, and tomorrow is not the same man, so that he that yesterday owed money today owes none, because he is not the same man.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Zuccone:] What years Fawn?
[Hercules:] Some fewer score wanting one.
[Zuccone:] A good sober age, is she wealthy?
[Hercules:] Very wealthy.
[Zuccone:] Excellent.
[Hercules:] She has three hairs on her scalp and four teeth in her head, a brow wrinkled and puckered like old parchment half burnt, she has had eyes, no woman's Jawbones are more apparent, her sometimes envious lips, now shrink in, and give her nose and her chin leave to kiss each other, very moistly as for her revered it seldom opens, but the very breath that flies out of it infects the fowls of the air, & makes them drop down dead, her breasts hang like cobwebs, her flesh will never make you cuckold, her bones may.
 [Zuccone:] But is she wealthy?
 [Hercules:] Very wealthy.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Quicksilver:] [...] turn good fellow, turn swaggering gallant, and let the Welkin roar, and Erebus also: Look not Westward to the fall of Don Phoebus, but to the East; Eastward Ho [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: (Enter Beatrice leading a Monkey after her).

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Quicksilver:] Eastward Ho; Holla ye pampered Jades of Asia.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Quicksilver:] Sfoot lend me some money, hast thou not Hyren here?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Securitie:] [...] at every shaking of a leaf, he falls into an agony, to think what danger his Ship is in on such a Coast, and so forth.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Sam:] [...] they call it "knighting" in London when they drink upon their knees.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Lear

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Edmund:] [...] Why brand they us
With "base," with "baseness," "bastardy," "base," "base,"
Who, in the lusty stealth of nature, take
More composition and fierce quality
Than doth within a dull, stale, tired bed
Go to th’ creating a whole tribe of fops
Got ’tween asleep and wake?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hercules:] For indeed, sir, a repressed fame mounts like a camomile, the more trod down, the more it grows [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Gonzago:] [...] anxoué e ampexou, (that's Greek to you now.)

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Don Zuccone:] [...] dost thou leer on me?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Donetta:] [...] my fools that were appointed to wait on Don Cupid have launched out their ship to purge their stomachs on the water [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hercules:] Sole lov'de of him [has been emended to "sole lord of Hymen" ]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Carthalon:] Upon whose tops the Roman eagles stretch'd
Their large spread wings, which fann'd the evening air
To us cold breath [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Syphax:] [...] Haste Negro, that this heap may know
Me and their wrong [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Carthalon:] [...] yet doubtful stood the fight [...]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Carthalon:] Then look as when a Falcon towers aloft
Whole shoals of fowl and flocks of lesser birds,
Crouch fearfully and dive some among sedge,
Some creep in brakes: so Massinissa's sword
Brandished aloft, tossd 'bout his shining cask,
Made stoop whole squadrons [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Erictho:] Here Syphax here, quake not, for know
I know thy thoughts, thou wouldst entreat our power [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Pompey:] […] Which bears a burden heavier than the heavens,
Under which steel-shouldered Atlas groans.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lear:] O, that way madness lies, let me shun that;
No more of that.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lear:] Poor naked wretches, wheresoe'er you are,
That bide the pelting of this pitiless storm, Your looped and windowed raggedness defend you
From seasons such as these? O, I have ta'en Too little care of this.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Edmund:] This is the excellent foppery of the world, that when we are sick in fortune (often the surfeits of our own behavior) we make guilty of our disasters the sun, the moon, and stars, as if we were villains on necessity; fools by heavenly compulsion; knaves, thieves, and treachers by spherical predominance; drunkards, liars, and adulterers by an enforced obedience of planetary influence; and all that we are evil in, by a divine thrusting on. An admirable evasion of whoremaster man, to lay his goatish disposition on the charge of a star! My father compounded with my mother under the Dragon’s tail, and my nativity was under Ursa Major, so that it follows I am rough and lecherous. Fut, I should have been that I am, had the maidenliest star in the firmament twinkled on my bastardizing.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Kent:] [...] My lord, if you will give me leave, I will tread this unbolted villain into mortar and daub the wall of a jakes with him.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Golding:] No, thou wilt undo thyself. Alas I behold thee with pity, not with anger; thou common shot-clog, gull of all companies: me thinks I see thee already walking in Moor fields without a Cloak, with half a Hat, without a band, a Doublet with three Buttons, without a girdle, a hose with one point and no Garter, with a cudgel under thine arm borrowing and begging three pence.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lear:] No, I will be the pattern of all patience;
I will say nothing.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ambitioso:] Over what roof hangs this prodigious comet
In deadly fire?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Macbeth:] [...] my single state of man [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lord:] [...] hear my love if not my counsel.
[Antifront explains his reasons for going away. The other character now wishes him all best] [Lord:] Unto your celsitude I wish, till their effects your hope may never fail.
[Antifront:] [Antifront now decides to disguise himself and concludes:] [...] cuor forte rompe cattiva sorte.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Spark:] Sure Ladies I must needs say th' instinct of this herb hath wrought in this Gentleman such a divine influence of good words, excellent discourse, admirable invention, incoparable wit: why I tell ye, when he talks, wisdom stands a mile off and dares not come near him, for fear a should shame her: but before a did use this Tobacco, a was the arrantest Woodcock that ever I saw.
[Petoune:] Indeed I was a very silly fellow.
[Ruffell:] Nay you were an arrant ass.
[Petoune:] Sure I was a fool.
[Knight:] Nay, you were a most monstrous puppy.
[Petoune:] Indeed I was an Idiot, a very Idiot.
[Piso:] By this light thou wert a most egregious coxcomb.
[Petoune:] Indeed I was, indeed I was.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ruffell:] Come signeur, put your hand to the pipe.
[Susan:] First you shall never while you live offer Lady or Gentlewoman an empty pipe.
[Petoune:] Never.
[Susan:] Secondly, you shall never make Tobacco your Idol, taking it in a morning before you say your prayers.
[Petoune:] Never.
[Susan:] Thirdly, you shall never in the praise of Tobacco disclose or dispraise by the way of making comparisons, the secrets of Ladies, or Gentlewomen, as repeating their distilled waters, their censing oils, or their smoothing unguents.
[Spark:] To this you swear.
[Petoune:] Most willingly.
[Susan:] Fourthly, you shall never come with your squibs & smoke-squirts amongst Ladies and Gentlewomen, flinging out fume at your Nostrils, as a whale doth salt-water, unless you be entreated by them.
[Petoune:] Never.
[Susan:] Fiftly, you shall presently convey yourself out of our company, never to come more near us, unless you be sent for.
[Petoune:] Never?
[Susan:] No never: so, let him kiss the pipe.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Spark:] What art?
[Fleer:] Poor.
[Ruffell:] Dost mean to live in this town?
[Fleer:] I'd be loth to die in't.
[Knight:] In what country wert born?
[Fleer:] In none.
[Knight:] Where then?
[Fleer:] In a Town.
[Knight:] What nation art?
[Fleer:] An Italian:
[Knight:] O then thou canst make glasses.
[Fleer:] Ay, and as wisemen as you Asses too, O are you there Piso? your father is my good Lord, but no more of that yet.
[Spark:] Why Signior, I hope you wonnot swagger?
[Fleer:] No, nor I care not greatly for them that do, for your swaggerer is but like your walking spur, a gingles much but he'll nev'r prick.
[Knight:] Why art so melancholy?
[Susan:] I'll hold my life he is in love with some waiting Gentlewoman.
[Fleer:] He's a mad fellow will love any of you all, longer then a pissing while.
[Piso:] Why camst thou out of Italy into England?
[Fleer:] Because England would not come into Italy to me?
[Piso:] Why art sad?
[Fleer:] Because I have cause.
[Piso:] Who dost follow?
[Fleer:] My nose.
[Spark:] Who dost serve?
[Fleer:] God.
[Ruff:! Who art towards?
[Fleer:] He that's before me.
[Spark:] What dost want?
[Fleer:] Money.
[Spark:] Nothing else?
[Fleer:] Yes.
[Spark:] What?
[Fleer:] A good service.
[Spark:] Shall I prefer thee?
[Fleer:] I cannot tell, tis as I like the man.
[Spark:] Nai't shall be to a couple of Gentlewomen of thine own Country.
[...]
[Spark:] What's thy name?
[Fleer:] Fleer.
[Spark:] What's thy profession?
[Fleer:] I have ever been a Courtier.
[Spark:] A Courtier! come Gentlemen, I like this fellow so well that I'll prefer him straight.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Fleer:] So I thought indeed, you cannot poison so well as we Italians, but you'll find a means to bring a man out of his life as soon.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Florida:] Faith well Madam, were not your Citizens, such heavy head fellows:
[Felecia:] Thats a sign they are no drunkards.
[Fleer:] Indeed Madam, drink lightens the head, the heart, the heels, the pot, the purse, but it makes heavy chamberpots, full bowels, and foul rooms enough.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Florida:] But how dost like the Court Fleer?
[Fleer:] Well enough, if they did not catch their meat so; it comes no sooner from Table, but t'one fellow has a fat Duck by the rump, t'other a slippery Eel by the tail, and an old Courtier that best knew the tricks on't, was mumbling of a Cunny in a corner alone by himself.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ruffell:] I did pray oftener when I was an Englishman, but I have not prayed often, I must confess since I was a Britain: but doost hear Fleer? canst tell me if an Englishman were in debt, whether a Britain must pay it or no?
[Fleer:] No, question-less no.
[Ruffell:] I'm glad of that, I hope some honest statute will come shortly, and wipe out all my scores.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Fleer:] His love to her? what Signor, in love with my Ladies Antient?
[Sparke:] Why her Ancient?
[Fleer:] Because she carries her colours for her, but tis in a box: but signor you shall have a good match on't, though she be not rich, yet she's an ancient woman and is able to get her living, by midwifery, and I can tell ye tis not the worst trade going, considering how young and old, and all do their good wills to set them a work, and tis a good hearing, better they get then the Lawyers, for your midwives live by the agreement between party and party, & the falling in of lovers, but the Lawyers live by the falling out of friends.
[Petoune:] I pray sir what may she be worth?
[Fleer:] Worth? let me see, she hath three yellow periwigs of her own: she hath a Pan with a short silver handle about the length of a Barbers syringe: she has a Looking-glass too, but that has plaid the prodigal Citizen with lier, tis broken, and much other goods of the same nature.
[Sparke:] But come Signor, how will you woo her?
[Petoune:] I will tell her she is so wise, that neither age nor time could cousen her of beauty.
[Fleer:] And by my faith that will doe well.
[Petoune:] I will tell her that I love her most for the whiteness of her skin.
[Fleer:] But you may not say the sweetness of her breath, for that stinks.
[Petoune:] I will praise the smallness of her fingers.
[Fleer:] But I assure you, you may better praise the length of her nails.
[Petoune:] I am afraid that being old she has a dry hand.
[Fleer:] That's certain, but she has a very moist nose, you may praise her for that [...]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Antifront

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Macbeth:] [to the Ghost] Thou canst not say I did it. Never shake
Thy gory locks at me.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Nan:] [...] and i'faith he was a neat lad too, for his beard was newly cut bare; marry it showed something like a Meadow newly mowed: stubble, stubble.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Fleer:] l, By my troth I took him for a Conjurer, when I first saw him, he talked so much of his soul and the Devil.
[Spark:] Why he sold his soul to the Devil man, for the velvet that lines his cloak.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: (When Piso and Havelittle face a trial for murder, Fleer disguises himself as the incapacitated judge Ferrio to provide an appropriate conclusion)

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Knight:] And how lives he with him.
[Fleer:] Faith like Thisbe in the play, a has almost kill'd himself with the scabbard [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: (Antifront disguises himself to preserve his daughters from degradation)

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ruffle:] What Gallants use to come to your house?
[Fleer:] All sorts, all nations, and all trades: there is first Master Gallant your Britaine, Master Metheglins your Welshman, Mousieur Mushroome the Frenchman: Signior Fumada the Spaniard, Master Oscabath the Irishman: and Master Shamrock his Lackey, O and Master Slopdragon the Dutchman. Then for your Tradesmen, there comes first Master Saluberrimum the Physican, Master Smooth the Silkman, Master Thimble the Tailor, Master Blade the Cutler, and Master Rowell the Spurrier: but Master Match the Gunner of Tower-hill comes often [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Fleer:] But believe me my little Gallants, ye play the Boys well.
[Nan:] Well? why I'll tell thee, I have played the boy so long as I am chang'd into the nature of a boy, I'll go to span counter with any page in Europe, for his best garters I can tell bawdy tales, drink drunk, brag, swear, and lie with any Lackey in the town.
[Susan:] I can man a punk to a play, or slander any Gentlewoman as well as any Inns of Court puny, I can as well as he, swear such a Lady is in love with me, and such a Citizen's Daughter would have come to bed to me, when all shall be as true as thy Ladies are honest.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Macbeth:] Who can be wise, amazed, temp’rate, and furious,
Loyal, and neutral, in a moment? No man.
Th' expedition of my violent love
Outrun the pauser, reason. Here lay Duncan,
His silver skin laced with his golden blood,
And his gashed stabs looked like a breach in nature
For ruin's wasteful entrance; there the murderers,
Steeped in the colors of their trade, their daggers
Unmannerly breeched with gore. Who could refrain
That had a heart to love, and in that heart
Courage to make 's love known?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: The Revenger's Tragedy

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: A prostitute marries a mercer.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: The Family of Love

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Doctor Glister:] And from what good exercise come you three.
[Gerardine:] From a play, where we saw most excellent Sampson excell the whole world in gate carrying.
[Dryfat:] Was it performed by the youths.
[Lypsalve:] By youths: why I tell thee we saw Sampson , and J hope 'tis not for youths to play Sampson : Believe it we saw Sampson bear the Town gates on his neck, from the lower to the upper stage, with that life and admirable accord, that it shall never be equalled (unless the whole new livery of Porters set their shoulders) [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Mistress Purge:] Husband, I see you are hoodwink'd in the right use of feeling and knowledge, as if I knew you not then, as well as the Child knows his own father [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Mistress Glister:] If he brings thee to a fool's paradise, he will forsake thee.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Fat paunches make leave pates, & grosser bits
Enrich the ribs but bankrupt quite the wits.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Lipsalve:] 'Tis my vocation, boy, we must never be weary of well-doing: love's as proper to a Courtier, as preciseness to a Puritane.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Prologue:] Speak natures language and not be withstood,
When with our Muse he saith that This is good [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Amada:] [...] I'll in to Julia, 'tis she and I
That must be Chorus in this Tragedy.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Bordello:] [...] Mercury had no good aspect in the horoscope of my nativity: women and lotus are recipiocall, their sauour is noysome.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: The water that God Mercury makes is in request with your lady.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Mulleasses:] [...] Image of death and daughter of the night,
Sister to Lethe, all oppressing sleep.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Eunuchus:] Why her's a slave in folio will seem to slight the love of a Princess, when he would willingly spend his talent on an oyster wife.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Wages:] Why they say the worlde is like a Bias bowl, and it runs all on the rich men's sides: others say, tis like a Tennis-ball, and fortune keeps such a Racket with it, as it tosses it in to time's hazard [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Young Lord:] O Wages! what Tennis-ball has fortune taken thee for: to toss thee thus into my way?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Marina:] [...] I trod upon a worm against my will,
But I wept for 't.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Antiochus:] [...] Her face, like heaven, enticeth thee to view
Her countless glory, which desert must gain;
And which without desert, because thine eye
Presumes to reach, all the whole heap must die.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Sir Oliver Smallshank:] We old men have our crotchets, our conundrums,
Our fegares, quirks and quibibles,
As well as youth, Justice Tutchim I go
To hunt no Buck, but prick a lusty Doe,
I go in truth a wooing.
[Justice Tutchin:] Then ride with me,
I'll bring you to my sister Somerfield.
[Sir Oliver Smallshank:] Justice not so: by her there hangs a Tale.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Throat:] [...] Dash, we must bear some brain to St. John's street, go, run, fly: and afar off enquire [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Frances:] Is there no trust,
No honesty in men.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Scudmore:] Whereas you write, my fortunes and my birth
Made above yours, may be a real cause
That I must leave you, know thou worthiest man,
Thou hast a soul, whose plenteous wealth supplies
All the lean wants blind Chance hath dealt to thee.
Yet could I think, the Goddess from all their store,
Who ne'er knew indigence unto their will,
Would (out of all their stock of Virtue left,
Or out of all new graces they can make)
Make such another piece as Scudmore is,
Then might he justly fear; but otherwise,
Sooner the Masculine Element of Fire,
Shall flame his Pyramids down to the Earth;
Sooner her Mountains shall swell up to Heaven,
Or softest April showers quench fires in Hell;
Sooner shall Stars from this Circumference,
Drop like false fairy exhalation,
Then I be false to vows made unto thee;
In whom, ought ne'er a fault: I ne'er could see,
But that you doubted once my constancy.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Scudamore:] How sweetly does your friendship play with mine
And with a simple subtlety, steals my heart
Out of my bosom.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Nevill:] [...] farewell worthy friend.
[Scudamore:] Nay look you, this same fashion does not please me,
You were not wont to make your visitation
So short and careless.
[Neville:] Tis your Jealousy
That makes you think it so [...] and so Good-morrow.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Neville:] [...] Yet think on't, keep thy secret, and thy friend
Sure and entire [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Nevill disguises himself as a parson to perform the double wedding ceremonies of the sisters Bellafront and Kate. This means that the marriages will be invalid and Nevill's friend Scudmore has a chance to win Bellafront, whom he loves.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Count Frederick:] Pendant thou'lt make me dote upon my self.
[Pendant:] Narcissus by this hand, had far less cause.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Strange:]: For some say some men on the back of Law,
May ride and rule it like a patient Ass,
And with a Golden Bridle in the mouth,
Direct it unto any thing they please.
Others report, it is a Spider's web,
Made to entangle the poor helpless Flies,
While the great Spiders that did make it first,
And rule it, sit i'th midst secure and laugh [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Sir Abraham:] Oh Sir, I was in love today, and could not eat, but here's one knows the case is alter'd, lend me but a Handkerchief to wipe my mouth, and I have done.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Castabella:] [...] be not displeas'd if on
The altar of his tomb I sacrifice
My tears.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[D'Amville:] Go, th' art the base corruption of my blood,
And like a tetter grow'st unto my flesh.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Pray frown, my lord; let me see how many wives you will have.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Sebastian:] [...] so you'll but put money i' my purse.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Sebastian:] [...] Th' hast trebles and basses enough, treble injury and base usage. But trebles and basses make poor music without means. Thou want'st means, dost?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Charlemont:] [...] This little world of man.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Guido Count of Arsena:] Sancta Maria! What thinkst thou of this change?
A Player's passion I'll believe hereafter,
And in a Tragic Scene weep for olde Priam,
 When fell revenging Pyrrhus with supposed
And artificial wounds mangles his breast,
And think it a more worthy act to me,
Than trust a female mourning ore her love:
Naught that is done of woman shall me please,
Natures step-children rather her desire.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Castabella:] O father, mercy is an attribute
As high as justice, an essential part
Of his unbound goodness, whose divine
Impression, form, and image man should bear.
And methinks man should love to imitate
His mercy, since the only countenance
Of justice were destruction, if the sweet
And loving favour of his mercy did
Not meditate between it and our weakness.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Cataplasma:] [...] What's here? A medlar with a plum tree gowing hard by it [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Sebastian:] [...] But here's a moral. A pop'ring pear tree growing upon the bank of a river [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [D'Amville:] Why doest thou stare upon me?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Angus:] Now does he feel
His secret murders sticking on his hands.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[D'Amville:] [...] but now that I begin to feel
The loathsome horror of my sin [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [D'Amville:] Mountains o'erwhelm me [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[D'Amville:] O were my body circumvolv'd
Within that cloud, that when the thunder tears
His passage open, it might scatter me
To nothing in the air!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Levidulcia:] [...] My strange affection to this man! 'Tis like
That natural sympathy which e'en among
The senseless creatures of the earth commands
A mutual inclination and consent.
For though it seems to be the free effect
Of mine own voluntary love, yet I
Can neither restrain it, nor give reason for 't.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Levidulcia:] [...] if they bid thee not welcome, they are very loggerheads.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Third Servant:] Why then take thy liquor. a health, Fresco! (kneels)

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[D'Amville:] [...] for the appetite
That steals her pleasures, draws the forces of
The body to an united strength and puts
'Em altogether into action,
Never fails of procreation.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Second Servant:] Do you take that in snuff, sir?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
