p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [D'Amville:] I'll tell thee what sha't do: knock him over the pate with thy torch; I'll bear thee out in't.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Levidulcia:] [...] Why sure their generation was asleep
When she begot those dormice, that she made
Them up so weakly and imperfectly.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Claridiana:] Slave, I will fight with thee at any odds,
Or name an instrument fit for destruction,
That e'er was made to make away a man,
I'll meet thee on the ridges of the Alps,
Or some inhospitable wilderness [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Levidulcia:] [...] I could unbrace and entertain
The air to cool it.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Abigal:] [...] one that (it seem'd) <span class="quote">fear'd no colours [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Lentulus:] Yet you sink apace sir.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Roberto:] [...] And taste a homely banquet we entreate.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Anna:] [...] I was the Indian, yet you had the treasure.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[D'Amville:] Dead be your tongues! Drop out
Mine eye-balls, and let envious Fortune play
At tennis with 'em. Have I liv'd to this?
Malicious Nature! Hadst thou born me blind,
Th'hadst yet been something favourable to me.
No breat? No motion? Prithee tell me, Heaven,
Hast shut thine eye to wink at murder, or
Hast put the sable garment on to mourn
At's death?
Not one poor spark in the whole spacious sky
Of all that endless number would vouchsafe
To shine? You viceroys to the king of Nature!
Whose constellations govern mortal births,
Where is that fatal planet rul'd at his
Nativity? That might ha' pleas'd to light
Him out, as well into th' world, unless
It be asham'd t' have been the instrument
Of such a good man's cursed destiny.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Don Sago:] [...] A hundred times in life a coward dies.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Don Sago:] [...] misers, that imprison'd gold
Within the harmless bowels of the earth.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[D'Amville:] [...] That rather than ha' trod upon a worm
He would ha'shunn'd the way [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[D'Amville:] That power of rule philosophers ascribe
To him they call the supreme of the stars,
Making their influences governors
Of sublunary creatures, when their selves
Are senseless of their operations [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Fresco:] [...] I bid him hang himself in his own garters.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Charlemont:] [...] Dreams are but the rais'd
Impressions of premeditated things,
By serious apprehension left upon
Our minds, or else th' imaginary shapes
Of objects proper to th' complexion or
The disposition of our bodies.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clermont:] Twas but your fancie then awaking dreame:
For as in sleepe, which bindes both th' outward senses,
And the sense common to; th' imagining power
(Stird vp by formes hid in the memories store,
Or by the vapours of o'er-flowing humours
In bodies full and foule; and mixt vvith spirits,)
Faines many strange, miraculous images,
In which act, it so painfully applyes
It selfe to those formes, that the common sense
It actuates with his motion; and thereby
Those fictions true seeme, and haue reall act:
So, in the strength of our conceits, awake,
The cause alike, doth of like fictions make.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hercules:] Behold, this monstrous rock thy death shall crown […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Melantius:] Why? wilt thou dote thyself out of thy life? Hence get thee to bed, have a careful looking to, and eat warm things and trouble not me: my head is full of thoughts more weighty than thy like of Death can be.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Bosola:] [...] We are merely the Stars' tennis balls (struck, and bandied
Which way please them) [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Atlas:] [...] whom it hath pleased fortune to make her tennis ball of, and therefore subject to be struck by every fool into hasard.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ferdinand:] [...] or doth thy friendship play
In this antipathous extreme with mine [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ferdinand:] [...] thy bosom binds some secret
Which do not trust me with [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Four Plays in One [Beaumont and Fletcher 1905 Glover edition volume 10, p. 38]" (William Peery. The Plays of Nathan Field: Edited from the Original Quartos with Introduction and Notes. Austin: The University of Texas Press, 1950. 244).

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Gerrard:] My Lords, the Law is but the great mans mule; he rides on it [...]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: What averse Star rul'd my nativity?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Helena:] [...] Was this wrinkled forehead
When 'twas at best, worth half so many lives?
Where is that beauty? lives it in this face
Which hath set two parts of the World at war,
Been ruin of the Asian Monarchy,
And almost this of Europe ? this the beauty
That launch'd a thousand ships from Aulis' gulf?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Chersogles:] Spreading his fearful ensigns in the air,
Like some prodigious comet, we may fear speedy revenge [...]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: This scene is very similar to Act 1, scene 2 in Nathan Field's A Woman is a Weather-Cock.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Alas, poore Booke, hunt not thou after prayse,
Nor dare to stretch thy hand vnto the Bayes
Vpon a Poets head: let it suffice
To thee and me, the world doth vs despise.
For 'tis a mad World, and it turnes on hinges,
Whilst some a birding goe, and set their springes
For to catch Woodcocks. Others sting and bite
Like Wasps and Mastiffs, and doe take delight
To quarrell with their shaddowes, nay, themselues,
And their owne broode.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Aymour:] Flatters, detracts, impaires, yet put it by,
Lest thou dear Lord (Narcissus-like) should dote
Upon thyself, and die; and rob the world
Of nature's copy, that she works form by.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Oriana:] Are all my hopes come to this? Is there no faith?
No troth? nor modesty in men?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Alexander:] No, no, no; I will not go down (makes himself unready) now I think on't.
[Widow:] Why, what do you mean, you will not be so uncivil to unbrace you here?
[Alexander:] By these Buckles I will, and what they will think on't [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Young Forester:] I have kild a man, but fairly as I am a Gentleman, without all base advantage in even tryal of both our desperate fortunes.
[Anne:] And hand to hand?
[Young Forester:] In single opposition.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [...] there, and rose again in Burgoigne. But the greater miracle is behind (for thereby hangs a tale.) This man sued a divorce, and was separated from his wife [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Bubulcus:] O that I were a flea upon his lip,
There would I suck for ever, and not skip.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Welborne:] They are well rewarded
That beggar themselves to make such cuckolds rich.
Thou viper, thankless viper; impudent bawd!
But since you are grow'n forgetful, I will help
Your memory, and tread thee into mortar:
 Not leave one bone unbroken.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Pynto:] Avant, I saw twelve dozen of Cuckolds in the middle region of the air, galloping on a black Jack, Eastward ho. [...] Now, now, now, my brains burn in Sulphur, and thus will I stalk about, and swim through a whole Element of dainty, neat, brisk, rich claret, canary, or maligo. Am not I Pynto, have not I hiren here? What art thou, a full moon, or a moon calf?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Duke:] Excellent wretch!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Clown:] I confess it; but whether you haue serv'd him well, or no, there hangs a Tale. Stro. How doth thy noble Lady, faire Lauret [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Athenais:] If I could leave my understanding to you,
It were superfluous to make division
Of whatsoever else I can bequeath you,
But to avoid contention, I allot
An equal portion of my possessions
To you my sons: but unto thee my daughter,
My joy, my darling (pardon me though I
Repeat his words) if my prophetic soul
Ready to take her flight, can truely guess at
Thy future fate, I leave the strange assurance
Of the greatness thou art born to, unto which
Thy brothers shall be proud to pay their service.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Athenais:] [...] shall I,
His vassal from obscurity rais'd by him
To this so eminent light, presume to appoint him
To do, or not to do this, or that: when wives
Are well aocommodated by their husbands
With all things both for use, and ornament,
Let them fix there, and never dare to question
Their wills or actions.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Annabella:] [...] Would thou hadst been lesse subject to those Stars
That luckless reign'd at my Nativity [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[D'Avolos:] A shrewd ominous token;
I like not that neither.
[Duke:] Again! What is't you like not?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Landrey:] Most true, you wept.
[Queen:] As a good Actor in a play would do,
Whose fancy works (as if he waking dreamt)
Too strongly on the Object that it copes with,
Shaping realities from mockeries;
And so the queen did weep. [...]
By this good night
I think I could become the Stage as well
As any she that sels her breath in publique.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Crotilda as the eunuch Castrato:] Is't even so, work and about my brain,
I'm lost for ever if not close again.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Clotair:] I'll take thy word, Eunuch, for the Kingdom's wealth.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Old Brissac:] Pray let me see the Ring; yes it was hers,
And she would say she'd never part with it
But when she meant to wed; if y'have married her,
Or have her promise riveted to yours,
Tell me but where she is, I'll be content,
For I in losing her have lost my joy.
[Charles Brissac:] Is she not then within?
[Old Brissac:] Yes too much; oh no
The house contains her not, she is not here,
Nor is for ought I know at all.
[Clovis the Prince:] O my prophetic soul, then 'tis no idle fear.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clotair:] Whom d'ye hold discourse with, the air?
Bethink yourself, this is no time to dally.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Eunuch:] [...] If (in her proud desire) I do prevent
Her lust this second time, before the third
She may repent and save her loathed soul,
Which my revenge would damn; yet were she crossed,
Her lust being now at full flood in her,
And no way left to quench her burning flame,
Her drier bones would make a bonfire,
Fit for the Devill to warm his hands by [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clovis:] I am no spirit; tast my active pulse,
And you shall find it makes such harmony
As youth and health enjoy.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: We desire forbidden things, and that is the perversenesse of your flesh, that will not be brideled with no lawful bounds, and wee see by experience that many men that have beautiful wives neglect their own better, and pray upon others more deformed. For Virtue as it never will be moved, though lewdness court it in the shape of heaven; So Lust, though to a radiant Angel linked, will sort itself in a terrestrial bed, and prey on garbage.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[...] Nay, I have done; beware of jealousy;
 I would not have you nourish jealous thoughts [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Crotilda as the eunuch Castrato:] King, thou hadst better far have strook thy Father,
Dig'd up his bones and plaid at logats with them.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clovis:] [...] Though she has broke her faith to me, to you
Against her reputation she'll be true [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Crotilda as the eunuch Castrato:] 'Tis true, I tell your Oracle;
There's not an hour's life between ye both;
 The poison's sure, I did prepare it for ye,
And have my self taken an Antidote [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clovis:] [...] The drowsy Poppy, cold Mandragora,
Or all the sleepy syrups of the world [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clotair:] The motions of the Sphæres move in that tongue.
Turn all your sables to the Tyrian dye,
Your dirges into sprightful wedding airs.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Second Soldier:] [...] The Monsieur, like the God of war, bestrides
A bounding Courser, who is therefore proud
To be so back'd, as knowing whom he bears:
So Centaur-like he's anchor'd to his seat,
As he had twind with the proud steed he rides on;
He grows unto his saddle all one piece,
And that unto his Horse; Sits like a Perseus on his Pegasus,
Stable and fleet.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Queen:] What French Neronian spirit have we here?
Insolent boy, wilt thou turn Parricide?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Clovis:] I'll tear him all to pieces then [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clotair:] [...] lock up in me
The Organs of remorse, all faculties
That write me man, or mankind; create
A spirit of horror in me, apt me to look
Upon such deeds nature would tremble at,
And the discreet composure of the world
Melt and dissolve to nothing, whilst I unmov'd
Smile at the alteration [...]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clothair:] [...] kiss me sweet,
[Kisses her.]
There's no deceit lies here [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Queen:] [...] But tell me Landrey, how did I play the mother;
Did not I seem a Niobe in passion,
A deluge of salt tears?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clovis:] [...] Oh King,
For I am swift as thought that executes.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clothair:] [...] It is not murder, tender-hearted fool
Which thou commitst, rather a sacrifice [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Queen:] I grant th'as great a Basilisk as he,
As thou art merely man; but as thy King
Divinity doth prop him, he stands firm
That builds on that foundation

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Queen:] [...] sure thou hast bought
A pair of cast lips of the chaste Diana's [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clotair:] [...] my passions but like lightning
Flash and away, dead e'er we say it is.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Aphelia:] I'll force a gentler nature in the steel,
And with my rainy eyes weep out their heat;
Which as it dies should hiss it self to scorn [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Clotair:] No more of that, it tends to madness [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Landrey:] Poor unfed sides that pass along the street,
I now am sensible of what ye want [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Queen:] Within the clothed circle of mine eyes,
Anchor thy fingers; alas, thy nails are par'd.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Queen:] Let thy hand sacrifice not butcher him.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Charles Brissac:] My noble Father -
[Old Brissac:] Tut, tut, tut! Noble me [no] nobles, nor Father me No Fathers.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Aphalia:] Commend me to my Lord.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Queen:] [...] Thy brother's ghost, young Clovis Ghost in arms
Has thrice appear'd to me this dismal night.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clotair:] My brother's spirit in arms, I swear it came forth here
Out of my Mothers Chamber as I knockt.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Crotilda as the eunuch Castrato:] Was it in Armour, said you?
[Clotair:] Yes in that Armor he was us'd to wear
When we have run at tilt.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Queen:] [...] Appearing in his Brother's warlike form [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Dumaine:] We are not safe Lamot; this bawdie peace
Begets a war within me; our swords worn
For Ornament, not use; the Drum & Trumpet
Sing drunken Carrols, and the Canon speaks
Health, not confusion [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Dumaine:] Hark, the thunder of the world, how out of tune.
This peace corrupting all things makes them speak.
What means this most adulterate noise?
[Lamot:] Why, are you ignorant?
This is a night of jubilee, and the King
Solemnly feasts for his war's happy success.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Clotair:] Oh see, it comes!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clovis:] What is it, Eunuch? [...] Though death stood gaping wide to swallow me,
I wold not shrink nor fear.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clotair:] What art thou that usurp'st this dead of night,
 In metal like the age? why art thou sent
To cast a horror on me?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clovis:] Hold, hold my heart - can I endure this -
Unhand me, Charles, and render me myself,
Lest I forget myself on thee.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clotair:] [...] let her sin
Be punish'd from above; I'll wait heaven's leisure.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Younger Pallatine:] Men o' the puissant Pike, follow the lights.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hannibal:] Like a perpetual comet to fright Rome
With his prodigious light.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Aurelio:] [...] Oh that I were a vail upon that face,
To hide it from the world; methinks I could
Envie the very Sun, for gazing on you!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Like Jove and Juno in a nuptial knot,
We'll knit the bands of Hymen, and outshine
The glorious Tapers of the golden Sun,
Whirl through the stately streets of spacious Rome
Like glistring Phaeton in an Orient chair.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
And nought so rich on either rock or shelf,
But, if unknown, lies useless to it self.
Therefore who thus doth make their secrets known,
Doth profit others, and not hurt his own.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Octavio:] My only child: I murmur'd against heaven
Because I had no more; but now I find
This one too many.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Nassuras:] Rare Rogue in Buckram, let me bite thee.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Cater:] Sure they are asleep, perhaps
The Slave being overleaven'd with his favour
Hath made himself stark drunk; we shall disturb
Our Lady and her Daughter, I much wonder
Mistris Nugella comes not to the door.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Some women are in Churches Saints or more,
Angels abroad, at home too like the Devil,
At windows Syrens, Parrots at the door;
And in their gardens Goats, or more uncivil:
And Tradesmen that were match till they have much,
In deadly danger are to meet with such.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: the mad boys that trail the puissant pike

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Gaselles:] [...] his buxom wife; who though she be not clad in Persian Silks, or costly Tyrian Purples,
has a clean skin, soft thighs, and wholesome corps,
fit for the trailer of the puissant Pike,
to solace in delight with.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Stand off, gentlemen, - let me see - which? Hum! this? - no; th'other! Hum! send for a lion and turn him loose; he won't hurt the true prince.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Common-curse:] Rare rogue in Buckram - thou shalt got out a wit, and vie with Martin Parker, or John Tailor.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Almanzor:] Why then we shall do all our work at once; I hate delays, let Fortune give me my Answer quickly, whether a Monarch or a Slave; - If my Stars have in this Fate this Crown, This day 'tis (aside) mine; if not, there's a hope lost.
[Clytus:] If you could produce the person of our King, my prophetick soul tells me the day were ours; such a signal Victory would make all their hearts turn Coward; the justice and vengeance they must expect from his injuries would wound farther and deeper than either Sword or Spear.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Rifaloro:] The scurvy Poet, giving each a Sonnet ,
Leaves only me without - But, by the faith
Of a Mahumetan, since thus he hath
Provok'd me to't, upon his skirts I'll sit:
Damn all his Matter, 'cause in Verse 'tis writ:
And, in defiance of the Triple Three,
Promote a Law, importing, that, to be,
Or not to be, a Poet; shall suffice
To prove, past doubt, one is not, or is, wise.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
This is a Spectacle of like Woe
To that of Juliet, and her Romeo.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Palamede:] That is onely, if the Servant were not found a man of this world; but if, upon trial, we had not lik'd each other, we had certainly left loving; and faith, that's the greater happiness of the two.
[Doralice:] 'Tis better as 'tis; we have drawn off already as much of our Love as would run clear; after possessing, the rest is but jealousies, and disquiets, and quarrelling, and piecing.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ulysses:] Thus we see ended all these fatal Broils,
The Plague of War, and Ten Years constant Toils -
First lend each noble Arm to lift in State,
This gallant Corps, and mourn Achilles Fate;
Then, like a Soldier, bear him to the Fleet,
Losing no time to court inconstant Gales,
But with glad Shouts fill all our empty Sails,
Turning our Joyful Eyes upon the Plain,
Where the sad Troy in Ashes does remain.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Torrismond:] Ten thousand Plagues consume him, Furies drag him,
Fiends tear him; Blasted be the Arm that strook,
The Tongue that order'd; - Onely She be spar'd
That hindred not the Deed. O, where was then
The Power that guards the Sacred Lives of Kings?
Why slept the Lightning and the Thunder-bolts,
Or bent their idle rage on Fields and Trees,
When Vengeance call'd 'em here?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Eugen:] The first missionaries of your Religion, bequeath'd but twelve Articles to be belliev'd by us and she has lately improved them into the jolly number of Falstaff's Buckram-men [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Melanax:] I told thee true:
But Lucifer, as he who foremost fell,
So now lies lowest in th'Abyss of Hell.
Chain'd till the dreadful Doom, in place of whom
Sits Beelzebub, Vicegerent of the damn'd,
Who listning downward hears his roaring Lord,
And executes his purpose, but no more
The morning creeps behind yon Eastern hill,
And now the Guard is mine, to drive the Elves
And foolish Fairies from their Moon-light Play,
And lash the Laggers from the sight of day.
(Descends.)

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Norfolk:] My Queen! my lovely Alban Queen! sure I'me
Already dead, and this the happy Place
Where Souls like hers receive their blest Rewards.
[Queen Mary:] Turn wretched Duke, or e're Death seals thy Eyes,
This moment tear 'em out, as I wou'd mine.
Shun me, as, if thou coud'st, thy horrid Fate,
Or a Goblin damn'd.
[Norfolk:] What says my Goddess Queen?
[Queen Mary:] Is not your wrong'd and mighty Spirit shockt?
And Death a much more welcome Guest than I?
And worse to see me than to feel the Blow?
[Norfolk:] By all your Wrongs and mine -

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Woman:] Here comes the Hell-bred Villain!
The father of this black and dismall Issue.
Moor do'st thou know this brat?
[Aron:] Yes, Princes be kind to't, 'tis of kin to you.
[Chiron:] Accursed Off-spring!
[Demetrius:] It shall not Live.
[Aron:] It shall not; Princes, for the love I bear to you and to the Empress, it shall not.
[Demetrius:] Give it me, my sword shall dispatch it,
[Aron.:] Let no hand but mine do Execution. (Aron takes the Child from the Woman).

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
I. "As you came from that holy land
Of Walsingham,
Met you not with my true love
By the way as you came?"
II. "How should I, Sir, your true love know,
 That have met many a one
As I came from that holy land,
That have come, that have gone?"

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [...] pith and marrow [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Truepenny

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Then his sentences must be well framed and his words aptly used through the whole discourse of his Oracion.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Vickers nonpubl CiceroDolman "if my sense shall be extinct, and my death resemble sleep, which often without any trouble of dreams, doth bring a man most quiet rest, (O Lorde) what pleasure shall death be to me!" (1.41.97; Sig. G6r). If it be true, Socrates continues, "that death is a departure into these regions, which all they inhabite, that are departed out of this life", then "this ought to seem a sweet pilgrimage" (1.41.98; Sig. G6r-v). Cicero reiterated these sentiments, wishing “that either men would hereafter desire death, ot at the least wise, cease to fear it. For if at the last day of our life, our souls die not, but only change their place, what ought we more to wish? But if death do utterly destroy us, what can be better, than in the rage of great storms, sweetly to slumber? and after that a man hath nodded out of this life, to sleep everlastingly.(1.49.117; Sig. H8r) The parallels [...] link up with Hamlet's later metaphor of death as "The undiscover'd country, from whose bourn / No traveller returns".

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Philautes to Euphues his son]: At thy comming into England, be not too inquisitive of news, neither curious in matters of State, in assemblies ask no questions, either concerning manners or me. Be not lavish of thy tongue, either in causes of weight, least thou shew thy self an espy-all, or in wanton talk, least thou prove thy self a fool. It is the Nature of that country to sift strangers, every one that shaketh thee by the hand is not joined to thee in heart. They think Italians Wanton, & Grecians subtile, they will trust neither, they are so incredulous, but undermine both, they are so wise. Be not querulous for every light occasion, they are impatient in their anger of any equal, ready to revenge an iniury, but never want to proffer any: they never fight without provoking, and once provoked, they never cease. Beware thou fal not into the snares of love, the women there are wise, the men crafty: they will gather love by thy looks, and pick thy mind out of thy hands. It shall be there better to hear what they say, then to speak what thou thinkest: They have long ears and short tongues, quick to hear, and slow to utter: broad eyes and light fingers, ready to espy and apt to strike.

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Aye, aye, my masters, you may mock on as you see cause, but I warrant you the good old truepenny Marprelate is not so merry; he sits ruminating under an oak, or in the bottom of a haystack, whose blood shall be first spilt in the reformation of the church.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: But least I might seem with these night crows, Nimis curious in aliena republica. I'll turn back to my first text, of studies of delight; and talk a little in friendship with a few of our trivial translators. It is a common practise now a days amongst a sort of shifting companions, that run through every art and thrive by none, to leave the trade of Noverint whereto they were born, and busy themselves with the endeavors of Art, that could scarcely latinise their neck-verse if they should have need; yet English Seneca read by candlelight yields many good sentences, as Blood is a beggar, and so forth: and if you intreat him fair in a frosty morning, he will afford you whole Hamlets, I should say handfuls of tragical speeches.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: The order of proceeding to judgment is by assent of voices, and open yielding their mind in court, the major part being preferred for sentence.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Perillus:] [...] But he, the mirror of mild patience,
Puts up all wrongs, and never gives reply [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [...] that were of hereafter shall be seized of any lands [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Sleep after toil, port after stormy seas,
Ease after war, death after life does greatly please.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: it is not lawful for ligatures to carve for themselves, taking their legacies at their own pleasures. [...] For he may not be his own carver in this case.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Long work it were,
Here to account the endless progeny
Of all the weeds, that bud and blossom there [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: In Adonis' garden is word "everlasting", the impossibility of complete dissolution, the changing form and fashion in all natural life, the hostility of Time to the flowering herbs and goodly things, and the distinction between reasonable souls and beasts.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
For thy she gave him warning every day,
The love of women not to entertain;
A lesson too too hard for living clay,
 Form love in course of nature to refrain [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lucifera] Sudden upriseth from her stately place
The royal Dame, and for her coach doth call [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: flower-garlanded, dew-trickling Medway at her bridal

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: "snowy Florimell", whose body "was purest snow in massie mould congeal'd" and whose face was mingled "with perfect vermily, That like a lively sanguine it seemed to the eye"

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Florimell can] hold a fool in vain delight
[...]
the Monster

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
And there a noble crew of lords and ladies stood on every side,
which with their presence fair, the place much beautified.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Scudamour's "dram of hony" in a similarly fluid metaphor (IV.x.I.I-5): True he it said, what euer man it sayd, That loue with gall and hony doth abound, But if the one be with the other wayd, For euery dram of hony therein found, A pound of gall doth ouer it redound. In suggesting "o'er-redound" as an emendation for [of a doubt] in Q2 I recall Milton's use of the word with a similar connotation (P.L. VII.56-59): But the evil soon Driv'n back redounded as a flood on those From whom it sprung, impossible to mix With Blessedness

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [...] a sea of troubles [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Una:] What worlds delight, or joy of living speech
Can heart, so plung'd in sea of sorrows deep [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Great troops of people travelled thitherward
Both day and night, of each degree and place,
But few returned, having scraped hard,
With baleful beggary, or foul disgrace,
Which ever after in most wretched case,
Like loathsome lazars, by the hedges lay.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[There is] no cautel under heaven, whereby the liberty of making or revoking his testament can be utterly taken away [...]
a man may as oft as he will make a new testament, even until the last breath, nether is there any cautel under the sun to prevent this liberty [...] neither is there any cautel under heaven to prevent this liberty, which also inureth whiles any life endureth.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Pyrochles [...] ne car'd for his saufgard,
But rudely rag'd and like a cruel Tigre far'd.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [When Pyrochles is unhorsed, he is compelled] to matchen equal fight

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Uplifting high, he weened with Morddure,
His own good sword Morddure, to cleave his head.
The faithful steel such treason no'uld endure,
But swerving from the mark, his Lord's life did assure.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Prince Arthur and his horse reel at the] fell [blow of Pyrochles]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
In their beginning they are weak and wan,
But soon through suff'rance grew to fearful end;
Whiles they are weak betimes with them contend:
For when they once to perfect strength do grow,
Strong wars they make, and cruel battry bend
Gainst fort of Reason, it to overthrow.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Anselmo:] [...] Or Amadine deserved her high extolment.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Richard:] Alas, that Warwick had no more forecast,
But whiles he thought to steal the single ten,
The King was slyly fingered from the deck.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King Henry:] Well, for this night we will repose us here.
Tomorrow toward London back again,
To look into this business thoroughly,
And call these foul offenders to their answers,
And poise the cause in Justice' equal scales,
Whose beam stands sure, whose rightful cause
prevails.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Herner:] Masters, I am come hither, as it were, upon my man’s instigation, to prove him a knave and myself an honest man; and touching the Duke of York, I will take my death I never meant him any ill, nor the King, nor the Queen. - And therefore, Peter, have at thee with a downright blow!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clifford:] Now, Richard, I am with thee here alone.
This is the hand that stabbed thy father York,
And this the hand that slew thy brother Rutland,
And here's the heart that triumphs in their death
And cheers these hands that slew thy sire and brother
To execute the like upon thyself.
And so, have at thee!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lucy:] Is Talbot slain, the Frenchmen's only scourge,
Your kingdom's terror and black Nemesis?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clarence:] To keep that oath were more impiety
Than Jephthah when he sacrificed his daughter.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Enter Segasto running and Amadine after him, <span class="quote">being pursued with a bear.]<span>

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Bolingbroke:] [...] Deep night, dark night, the silent of the night,
The time of night when Troy was set on fire,
The time when screech owls cry and bandogs howl,
And spirits walk, and ghosts break up their graves -
That time best fits the work we have in hand.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [...] walking spirits which have been so much talked of in time of popery, and were taken for the souls of them which were dead [...] whether the souls of men departed walk after death and appear unto men, exhorting them unto this or that.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Richard:] Fie! Charity, for shame! Speak not in spite,
For you shall sup with Jesu Christ tonight

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [King Henry VI:] First for thy heinous crimes, thou shalt two days in London do penance barefoot in the streets, with a white sheet about thy body, and a wax Taper burning in thy hand.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Giordano:] Why do you stand bare-headed? You do yourself wrong.
[Edward:] Pardon me, good sir, I do it for my ease.
[Giordano:] I pray you be covered, you are too ceremonious.
[Edward:] I am so well, that me thinks I am in heaven.
[Giordano:] If you love me, put on your hat.
[Edward:] I will do it to obey you, not for any leisure that I take in.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Anselmo:] [...] Whether report gilded a worthless Trunk [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Then, if we had seen a man go wallowing in the streets, or line sleeping under the board, we would have spat at him as a toad, and called him [a] foul drunken swine [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Demetrius:] [...] Though Bassianus be the Emperor’s brother,
Better than he have worn Vulcan's badge.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Bianca:] What, master, read you? First resolve me that.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Thus walks he up and down in his Majesty, taking a yard of ground at every step, and stamps on he earth so terribly, as if he meant to knock up spirits, when (foul drunken bezzle) if an Englishman set his little finger to him, he falls like a hogs-trough that is set on one end.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Grumio:] Out of their saddles into the dirt, <span class="quote">and thereby hangs a tale.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Clim of the Clough [the devil] thou that usest to drink nothing but scalding lead and sulphur in hell, thou art not so greedy of thy night gear. O, but thou hast a foul swallow, if it come once to carousing of human blood; but that's but seldom [...] otherwise thou art tide at rack and manger, and drinkest nothing but the Aqua vitae of vengeance all thy life time [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [...] the heavy headed gluttonous house-dove [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Sloth and sluggish security [...].

[...] neglect [...] dallying [...] indignities [...] love-dream [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: I will not forget the old wives logick, when Adam delved and Eve spanne, who was then a Gentleman?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Duke:] [...] Go, some of you, knock at the abbey gate [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Edward:] I cannot brook these haughty menaces […]

[Edward:] Cease brother, for I cannot brook these words […]

[Gaveston:] My Lord I cannot brook these iniuries.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: A mighty deformer of men's manners and features, is this unnecessary vice of all other. Let him be indued with never so many virtues, and have as much goodly proportion and favour as nature can bestow upon a man; yet if he be thirsty after his own destruction, and hath no joy nor comfort, but when he is drowning his soul in a gallon pot, that one beastly imperfection will utterly obscure all that is commendable in him; and all his good qualities sink like lead down to the bottom of his carousing cups, where they will lie, like lees and dregs, dead and unregarded of any man.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: For besides, nature hath left him a flaberkin face, like one of the four winds, and cheeks that sag like a woman's dugs over his chin-bone, his apparel is so put up with bladders of Taffeta, and his back like beef stuffed with Parsley, so drawn out with Ribands and deuces, and blistered with light sarcenet bastings, that you would think him [a Dane] nothing but a swarm of Butterflies, if you saw him a far off.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: The Danes are bursten-bellied sots, that are to be confuted with nothing but Tankards or quart-pots, and Ovid might as well have read his verses to the Geese that understood him not, as a man talk reason to them that have no ears but their mouths nor sense but of that which they swallow down their throats. God so love me, as I love the quick-witted Italians, and therefore love them more, because they mortally detest this surley swinish Generation.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Men when they are idle, and know not what to do, saith one let us go to the Steelyard and drink Rhenish wine. Nay, if a man knew where a good whorehouse were saith another, it were somwhat like. Nay saith the third, let us go to a dicing-house or a bowling alley, and there we shall have some sport for our money.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Besides, my vagrant Reveller haunts Plays, & sharpens his wits with frequenting the company of Poets; he emboldens his blushing face by courting fair women on the sudden, and look into all Estates, by conversing with them in public places. Now tell me whether of these two, the heavy-headed gluttonous house dove, or this lively wanton young Gallant, is likely to prove the wiser man, and better member in the Common-wealth.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Sloth in Nobility, Courtiers, Scholars, or any men is the chiefest cause that brings them in contempt. For as industry and unfatigable toil raiseth mean persons from obscure houses to high thrones of authority: so Sloth and sluggish security causeth proud Lords to tumble from the towers of their starry descents, and be trodden underfoot of every inferior Bosnian. […] The only enemy to Sloth is contention and emulation; as propose one man to myself, that is the only mirror of our Age, and strive to out-go him in virtue.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: That is the course he that will be popular must take, which if he neglect, and sit dallying at home, nor will be awaked by any indignities out of his love-dream, but suffer every upstart groom to defy him, set him at naught, and shake him by the beard unrevenged, let him straight take orders and be a Churchman, and then his patience may pass for a virtue, but otherwise he shall be suspected of cowardice, and not car'd for of any.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Edward:] [...] Gallop apace, bright Phoebus, through the sky,
And, dusky Night, in rusty iron car [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Saturninus:] [...] My lords, you know, as know the mightful gods,
However these disturbers of our peace
Buzz in the people's ears, there naught hath passed
But even with law against the willful sons
Of old Andronicus.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Younger Mortimer:] [...] Farewell, fair queen. Weep not for Mortimer,
That scorns the world, and, as a traveller,
Goes to discover countries yet unknown.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Young Lucius:] Grandsire, 'tis Ovid's Metamorphosis.
 My mother gave it me.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King Richard:] For God's sake, let us sit upon the ground
And tell sad stories of the death of kings -
How some have been deposed, some slain in war […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King Richard:] Let me unkiss the oath twixt thee and me;
And yet not so, for with a kiss 'twas made. -
Part us, Northumberland […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[York:] […] Mounted upon a hot and fiery steed,
Which his aspiring rider seemed to know […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ghosts of Princes:] Sleep, Richmond, sleep in peace and wake in joy.
Good angels guard thee from the boar's annoy.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Richard:] Go, gentlemen, every man unto his charge.
Let not our babbling dreams affright our souls.
Conscience is but a word that cowards use,
Devised at first to keep the strong in awe.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Gaunt:] Things sweet to taste prove in digestion sour.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Richard:] Thou sing’st sweet music. Hark, come hither, Tyrrel.
Go, by this token. Rise, and lend thine ear.
There is no more but so. Say it is done,
And I will love thee and prefer thee for it.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Buckingham:] My hair doth stand an end to hear her curses.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: To the most honoured and virtuous, beautified lady, the lady Elizabeth Carey

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Richard:] He was the right, and so indeed it is.
Tell the clock there. Give me a calendar.
Who saw the sun today?
 [Ratcliffe:] Not I, my lord.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Richmond:] The father rashly slaughtered his own son;
The son, compelled, been butcher to the sire.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Richard:] Give me another horse! Bind up my wounds!
Have mercy, Jesu! - Soft, I did but dream.
O coward conscience, how dost thou afflict me!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Duchess:] Dead life, blind sight, poor mortal living ghost,
Woe’s scene, world’s shame, grave’s due by life usurped,
Brief abstract and record of tedious days,
 Rest thy unrest on England’s lawful earth,
Unlawfully made drunk with innocent blood.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
I have a fine bow, and an ivory arrow:
And if thou miss, yet meat thou shalt lack,
I'll hang a bag and bottle at thy back.

Wilt thou set springs in a frosty Night,
To catch the long-billed Woodcock and the Snipe?
(By the bright glimmering of the Starry light)
The Partridge, Phaesant, or the greedy Crype?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Bonny Sweet Robin

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [...] because they fear not death, they shold fear something after death [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
For princes are the glass, the school, the book,
Where subjects' eyes do learn, do read, do look.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: If of a number of shreds of his sentences he can shape an oration, from all the world he carries it away, although in truth it be no more than a fool's coat of many colours.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Mercutio:] For this driveling love is like a great natural that runs lolling up and down to hide his bauble in a hole.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Juliet:] How camest thou hither, tell me, and wherefore?
The orchard walls are high and hard to climb,
And the place death, considering who thou art,
If any of my kinsmen find thee here.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Nurse:] There's no trust
No faith, no honesty in men.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Mowbray:] [...] And now my tongue's use is to me no more
Than an unstringèd viol or a harp, up
Or, being open, put into his hands
That knows no touch to tune the harmony.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Richard:] Must I do so? And must I ravel out
My weaved-up follies?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Bolingbroke:] Go, some of you, and fetch a looking-glass.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Tybalt:] What, drawn and talk of peace? I hate the word
As I hate hell, all Montagues, and thee.
Have at thee, coward!

[Romeo:] Wilt thou provoke me? Then have at thee, boy!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Nurse:] [...] I do bear a brain.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Nurse:] [...] if you should lead her into a fool's paradise, as they say, it were a very gross kind of behavior, as they say.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Romeo:] See how she leans her cheek upon her hand.
O, that I were a glove upon that hand,
 That I might touch that cheek!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Nurse:] Even or odd, of all days in the year
 Come Lammas Eve at night shall she be fourteen. [...]
And she was weaned (I never shall forget it)
Of all the days of the year, upon that day.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Gardener:] Poor queen, so that thy state might be no worse,
I would my skill were subject to thy curse.
Here did she fall a tear. Here in this place
I'll set a bank of rue, sour herb of grace.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [First Watch:] Go, some of you; whoe'er you find, attach.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Bolingbroke:] Go, some of you, convey him to the Tower.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Mercutio:] [...] Now will he sit under a medlar tree
And wish his mistress were that kind of fruit
As maids call medlars when they laugh alone.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Mercutio:] [...] O Romeo, that she were, O, that she were
An open-arse, thou a pop'rin pear.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Oberon:] [...] So shall all the couples three
Ever true in loving be,
And the blots of Nature's hand
Shall not in their issue stand.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Romeo:] […] Dry sorrow drinks our blood.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Lady Capulet:] Ay, sir, but she will none, she gives you thanks.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lysander:] [...] I have a widow aunt, a dowager
Of great revenue, and she hath no child.
From Athens is her house remote seven leagues,
And she respects me as her only son.
There, gentle Hermia, may I marry thee;
And to that place the sharp Athenian law
Cannot pursue us.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Juliet:] Too like the lightning, which doth cease to be
Ere one can say "It lightens."

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Benvolio:] He swung about his head, and cut the winds,
Who, nothing hurt withal, hiss'd him in scorn.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Capulet:] Wife, we scarce thought us blessed
That God had lent us but this only child,
But now I see this one is one too much,
And that we have a curse in having her.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Oberon:] [...] And this ditty, after me
Sing and dance it trippingly.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Romeo and Juliet

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Friar:] And nought so rich on either rock or shelf,
But, if unknown, lies uselesse to it self.
Therefore who thus doth make their secrets known,
Doth profit others, and not hurt his own.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Prince:] For never was a story of more woe
Than this of Juliet and her Romeo.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[York:] I have had feeling of my cousin's wrongs
And labored all I could to do him right.
But in this kind to come, in braving arms,
Be his own carver and cut out his way
To find out right with wrong, it may not be.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Juliet:] O, bid me leap, rather than marry Paris,
From off the battlements of any tower,
Or walk in thievish ways, or bid me lurk
Where serpents are. Chain me with roaring bears,
Or hide me nightly in a charnel house,
/ O’ercovered quite with dead men’s rattling bones,
With reeky shanks and yellow chapless skulls.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Prologue:] [...] From forth the fatal loins of these two foes
A pair of star-crossed lovers take their life;
Whose misadventured piteous overthrows
Doth with their death bury their parents' strife.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
But if these eyes of yours, (load-stars of Love,
Showing the World's great dance to your mind's eye!)
Cannot with all their demonstrations move
Kind apprehension in your fantasy,
Of dancing's virtue, and nobility:
How can my barbarous tongue win you there to
Which Heau'n and Earth's fair speech could never do?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King:] Berowne is like an envious sneaping frost
That bites the firstborn infants of the spring.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Let us therefore pray that we be not miscarried by the deceits of the wicked pilot Satan, whose directions are merely indirect, and whose sails are deceitful, being glorious to the eye; and the bark wherein he carrieth his unhappy passengers seemeth to be a most secure cradle, gliding on without tempest or wave, until it come to the end of their race, where, alas! they fall into the gulf of perpetual perdition. Such a master is he, and such mariners are his false prophets, that they delight flesh and blood, and all their course seemeth sweet, but short: and sour merchandise shall they have, that pass in the pinnace of his poisoned errors.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Armado:] Call’st thou my love "hobby-horse"?
[Boy:] No, master. The hobby-horse is but a colt, and your love perhaps a hackney.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Pandulph:] The better act of purposes mistook
Is to mistake again; though indirect,
Yet indirection thereby grows direct,
And falsehood falsehood cures, as fire cools fire
Within the scorchèd veins of one new-burned.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [King Philip:] It likes us well.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Catechysius the Hermit:] Now all is but the action of the Mind,
That rectifi'd, the rest is all but wind.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Bastard:] By heaven, these scroyles of Angiers flout you, kings,
And stand securely on their battlements
As in a theater, whence they gape and point
At your industrious scenes and acts of death.
Your royal presences, be ruled by me:
Do like the mutines of Jerusalem,
Be friends awhile, and both conjointly bend
Your sharpest deeds of malice on this town.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Portia:] [...] [I'll] prove the prettier fellow of the two,
And wear my dagger with the braver grace,
And speak between the change of man and boy
With a reed voice, and turn two mincing steps
Into a manly stride, and speak of frays
Like a fine bragging youth, and tell quaint lies
How honorable ladies sought my love,
Which I denying, they fell sick and died -
I could not do withal! - then I'll repent,
And wish, for all that, that I had not killed them.
And twenty of these puny lies I'll tell,
That men shall swear I have discontinued school
Above a twelvemonth.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Berowne:] [...] Well, I do nothing in the world but lie, and lie in my throat.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [King:] [...] But to the place where. It standeth north-north-east and by east from the west corner of thy curious-knotted garden. There did I see that low-spirited swain, that base minnow of thy mirth [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King Philip:] [...] Our cannons' malice vainly shall be spent
Against th'invulnerable clouds of heaven.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Berowne:] But love, first learnèd in a lady’s eyes,
Lives not alone immurèd in the brain,
But with the motion of all elements
Courses as swift as thought in every power,
And gives to every power a double power,
Above their functions and their offices.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Pembroke:] Indeed, we heard how near his death he was
Before the child himself felt he was sick.
This must be answered either here or hence.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: The proper end of conscience is, to determin of things done. And by this one thing, conscience is distinguished from all other gifts of the mind as intelligence opinion, science faith, prudence. Intelligence simply conceives a thing to be or not to be: science judgeth it to be certain and sure: faith is a persuasion, whereby we believe things that are not [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Falstaff:] Now, my masters, happy man be his dole, say I. Every man to his business.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Shallow:] Bodykins, Master Page, though I now be old and of the peace, if I see a sword out, my finger itches to make one.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hostess Quickly:] No, thou arrant knave. I would to God that I might die, that I might have thee hanged. Thou hast drawn my shoulder out of joint.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Falstaff:] What, upon compulsion? Zounds, an I were at the strappado or all the racks in the world, I would not tell you on compulsion. Give you a reason on compulsion? If reasons were as plentiful as blackberries, I would give no man a reason upon compulsion, I.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Falstaff:] Will you tell me, Master Shallow, how to choose a man? Care I for the limb, the thews, the stature, bulk, and big assemblance of a man! Give me the spirit, Master Shallow.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Fallstaff:] [sings] When Arthur first in court -
[To Will] Empty the Jordans [Will exits]
And was a worthy king -

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Shallow:] Yea, Davy, I will use him well. A friend i' th' court is better than a penny in purse. Use his men well, Davy, for they are arrant knaves and will backbite.
[Davy:] No worse than they are back-bitten, sir, for they have marvelous foul linen.
[Shallow:] Well-conceited, Davy. About thy business, Davy.
[Davy:] I beseech you, sir, to countenance William Visor of Woncot against Clement Perkes o’ th’ hill.
[Shallow:] There is many complaints, Davy, against that Visor. That Visor is an arrant knave, on my knowledge.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Comedy:] How some damned tyrant to obtain a crown,
Stabs, hangs, poisons, smothers, cuts throats,
And then a Chorus too comes howling in,
And tells us of the worrying of a cat,
Then of a filthy whining ghost,
Lapt in some foul sheet, or a leather pelt,
Comes screaming like a pig half sticked,
And cries Vindicta, revenge, revenge:
With that a little rose flashes forth,
Like smoke out of a Tobacco pipe, or a boys squib:
Then comes in two or three like to drovers,
With tailors bodkins, stabbing one another,
Is not this trim? is not here goodly things?
That you should be so much accounted of,
I would not else.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King:] [...] Let all the tears that should bedew my hearse
Be drops of balm to sanctify thy head;
Only compound me with forgotten dust.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Glendower:] I cannot blame him. At my nativity
The front of heaven was full of fiery shapes,
Of burning cressets, and at my birth
The frame and huge foundation of the Earth
 Shaked like a coward.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hotspur:] And I can teach thee, coz, to shame the devil
By telling truth. Tell truth and shame the devil.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Dogberry:] I leave an arrant knave with your Worship, which I beseech your Worship to correct yourself, for the example of others.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Bobadill:] […] sure I was struck with a planet thence, for I had no power to touch my weapon.
[Ed. Knowell:] I, like enough, I have heard of many that have been beaten under a planet: go, get you to a surgeon.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Benedick:] And do it with all thy heart.
[Beatrice:] I love you with so much of my heart that none is left to protest.
[Benedick:] Come, bid me do anything for thee.
[Beatrice:] Kill Claudio.
[Benedick:] Ha! Not for the wide world.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Margaret:] Well, an you be not turned Turk, there's no more sailing by the star.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Verges:] Marry, sir, our watch tonight, excepting your Worship's presence, ha' ta'en a couple of as arrant knaves as any in Messina.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
From the black kingdom of infernal Dis [...]
And from the dungeon of the dark abyss,
Wherein the Ocean Seas of troubles slow,
I do ascend upon this worldly stage [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Benedick:] O God, sir, here's a dish I love not! I cannot endure my Lady Tongue.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: And my prophetic soul doth truly say [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
He's but a sponge, and shortly needs must lease
His wrong got juice, when greatness' fist shall squeeze
His liquor out.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Then, boyling Wrath, stern, cruell, swift, and rash,
That like a Boar her teeth doth grinde and gnash:
Whose hair doth stare, like bristled Porcupine;
Who som-times rowles her ghastly-glowing eyn,
And som-time fixtly on the ground doth glaunce,
Now bleak, then bloody in her Countenance [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Andrugio:] [...] Sing Mellida is dead, all hearts will relent
[...] in sad condolement at that heavy sound [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Brutus:] […] Let's be sacrificers, but not butchers […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Pistol:] O, Seigneur Dew should be a gentleman.
Perpend my words, O Seigneur Dew, and mark:
O Seigneur Dew, thou diest on point of fox, except, O
Seigneur, thou do give to me egregious ransom.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Antony:] This was the noblest Roman of them all.
All the conspirators save only he
Did that they did in envy of great Caesar.
He only in a general honest thought
And common good to all made one of them.
His life was gentle and the elements
So mix'd in him that Nature might stand up
And say to all the world "This was a man!".

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Mellida:] [...] well point our speech
With amorous kissing, kissing commas [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Titinius:] [...] By your leave, gods, this is a Roman's part.
Come, Cassius sword, and find Titinius' heart!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Soldier:] My Lord,
The battle of the Spaniards is dispersed:
Beside, I bring to you this happy news,
The worthy Duke of Boulogne long desired,
And much bewailéd for his injury,
Lives and returned about an hour since.
At his first coming, armed in complete steel,
 Challeng'd the Duke Medyna at his Tent,
And there in single combat like himself,
And like a father of his country's weal,
Hath slain that proud disturber of our peace [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Firke:] I speak it in secret, mistress Rose, and he are by this time: no not so, but shortly are to come over one another with, Can you dance the shaking of the sheets?

[Eyre:] [...] mark this old wench, my king, I danced the shaking of the sheets with her six and thirty years ago.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King Henry:] [...] We are but warriors for the working day;
Our gayness and our gilt are all besmirched
With rainy marching in the painful field.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Westmoreland:] How smooth and even they do bear themselves,
 As if allegiance in their bosoms sat
Crownèd with faith and constant loyalty.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Brutus:] [...] Ha, who comes here?
I think it is the weakness of mine eyes
That shapes this monstrous apparition.
It comes upon me. - Art thou any thing?
Art thou some god, some angel, or some devil,
That mak’st my blood cold and my hair to stare?
Speak to me what thou art.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Calphurnia:] [...] And ghosts did shriek and squeal about the streets.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [King Henry:] [...] My ransom is <span class="quote">this frail and worthless trunk</sapn> [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Polonius:] Perpend.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Come, ye heavy states of night,
Doe my father's spirit right,
Soundings baleful let mee borrow,
Burthening my song with sorrow,
Come sorrow come her eyes that sings,
By thee turned into springs.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Claudius:] But now, my cousin Hamlet, and my son - [...]
[Hamlet:] Not so, my lord; I am too much i' the sun.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Player King:] Full thirty times hath Phoebus' cart gone round [...]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ghost:] [...] And duller shouldst thou be than the fat weed
That roots itself in ease on Lethe wharf [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ophelia:] There's rosemary, that's for remembrance.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ghost:] [...] O Hamlet, what a falling off was there!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ghost:] [...] And in the porches of my ears did pour
The leprous distilment [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Antonio:] Resolved hearts, time curtails night,
opportunity shakes us his foretop.
Steel your thoughts, sharp your resolve,
imbolden your spirit, grasp your swords; alarum mischief,
& with an undated brow, out scout the grim opposition
Of most menacing peril.
Hark here, proud pomp shoots mounting triumph up,
Born in loud accents to the front of Jove.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ghost:] [...] And with a sudden vigor it doth posset
And curd [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ghost:] [...] And a most instant tetter barked about [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: (Enter Antonio with a book, Lucio, Alberto; Antonio in black)

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: (Enter Hamlet in black, reading a book)
