p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Queen:] No more!
[Hamlet:] A king of shreds and patches -
(Enter Ghost)
Save me and hover o'er me with your wings, You heavenly guards! - What would your gracious figure?
[Queen:] Alas, he's mad.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Maria:] What, my good boy, stark mad?
[Antonio:] I am not.
[Maria:] Alas, is that strange news? [...]
[Maria:] Alas my son's distraught. Sweet boy appease
Thy mutining affections.
 [Antonio:] By the astoning terror of swart night,
By the infectious damps of clammy graves,
And by the mould that presseth down
My dead father's skull: I'll be reveng'd.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Antonio:] [...] Blood cries for blood, and murder murder craves.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] What is he whose grief Bears such an emphasis, whose phrase of sorrow Conjures the wand’ring stars and makes them stand Like wonder-wounded hearers? This is I, Hamlet the Dane.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] Roasted in wrath and fire,
And thus o'ersizèd with coagulate gore [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Pandulpho:] [...] Yet I am less than a man. I am the miserables soul that breathes.
[Antonio:] 'Slid, sir, ye lie! by h'heart of grief, thou lies! I scorn't that any wretched should survive Outmounting me in that superlative: Most miserable, most unmatched woe. Who dare assume that, but Antonio?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [First Player:] [...] Repugnant to command. Unequal matched [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[First player:] For lo, his sword,
Which was declining on the milky head
Of reverend Priam, seemed i' th' air to stick.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Andrugio:] The fist of strenuous vengeance is clutched [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Andrugio:] [...] now is his fate grown mellow,
Instant to fall into the rotten jaws
Of chap-fall'n death.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] If thou dost marry, I'll give thee this plague for thy dowry: be thou as chaste as ice, as pure as snow, thou shalt not escape calumny. Get thee to a nunnery, farewell. Or if thou wilt needs marry, marry a fool, for wise men know well enough what monsters you make of them.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] Compounded it with dust, whereto 'tis kin.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:]<span class="quote"> Ay, truly, for the power of beauty will sooner transform honesty from what it is to a bawd than the force of honesty can translate beauty into his likeness. This was sometime a paradox, but now the time gives it proof. I did love you once.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ophelia:] Lord Hamlet, with his doublet all unbraced,
No hat upon his head, his stockings fouled,
Ungartered, and down-gyvèd to his ankle,
Pale as his shirt, his knees knocking each other […]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Rosencrantz:] Take you me for a sponge, my lord?
[Hamlet:] Ay, sir, that soaks up the king's countenance [...]
when he needs what you have gleaned, it is but squeezing you, and sponge, you shall be dry again.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Polonius:] […] That he's mad, 'tis true; 'tis true 'tis pity,
And pity 'tis 'tis true - a foolish figure […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Claudius:] [...] the distracted multitude [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Claudius:] <span class="quote">To bear all smooth and even [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Polonius:] [...] the most beautified Ophelia -
That's an ill phrase, a vile phrase; "beautified" [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: So sleep of death ends all our wretchedness.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [King Claudius:] For like the hectic in my blood rages [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Queen:] Sweets to the sweet, farewell!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ophelia:] Rich gifts wax poor when givers prove unkind.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ophelia:] How should I your true love know
From another one?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Alberto:] [...] There is a thing called scourging Nemesis.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ophelia:] [...] He is dead and gone, lady,
He is dead and gone.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Antonio:] [...] Me thinks I pass upon the front of Jove,
And kick corruption with a scornful heel,
Griping this flesh, disdain mortality.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] A broken voice, and his whole function suiting
With forms to his conceit? and all for nothing!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] Nay, but to live
In the rank sweat of an enseamèd bed,
Stewed in corruption, honeying and making love
Over the nasty sty!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] Man delights not no, nor woman neither, though by your smiling [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ophelia:] [...] there's rue for you; and here's some for me: we may call it herb-grace o' Sundays [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Barnado:] Last night of all,
When yond same star that's westward from the pole
Had made his course t' illume that part of heaven
Where now it burns [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] And still your fingers on your lips, I pray.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] I have of late, but wherefore I know not, lost all my mirth, forgone all custom of exercises [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] Making night hideous; and we fools of nature
So horridly to shake our disposition
With thoughts beyond the reaches of our souls?
[...]
But that the dread of something after death,
The undiscover'd country from whose bourn
No traveller returns, puzzles the will.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Claudius:] There's such divinity doth hedge a king,
That treason can but peep to what it would,
Acts little of his will [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] Look here, upon this picture, and on this [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] [...] Is it not monstrous that this player here,
But in a fiction, in a dream of passion,
Could force his soul so to his own conceit
That from her working all his visage wanned,
Tears in his eyes, distraction in his aspect, [...]

[Hamlet:] [...] Would not this, sir, and a forest of feathers (if the rest of my fortunes turn Turk with me) with two Provincial roses on my razed shoes, get me a fellowship in a cry of players?
[Horatio:] Half a share.
[Hamlet:] A whole one, I.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Francisco:] Not a mouse stirring.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] For use almost can change the stamp of nature
And either [...] the devil or throw him out
With wondrous potency.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
O brawling love, O loving hate,
O anything of nothing first created,
O heavy lightness, serious vanity,
Misshapen Chaos of well seeing forms
Feather of lead, bright smoke, cold fire, sickness, health,
Still waking sleep [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Ghost:] [...] And each particular hair to stand an end [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Peace:] [...] What is a man superior to a beast
But for his mind? nor that ennobles him,
While he dejects his reason; making it
The slave unto his brutish appetite.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Horatio:] [...] In the most high and palmy state of Rome,
A little ere the mightiest Julius fell,
The graves stood tenantless, and the sheeted dead
Did squeak and gibber in the Roman streets [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Rosalind:] A lean cheek [...] a blue eye and sunken [...] a beard neglected [...] Then your hose should be ungartered, your bonnet unbanded, your sleeve unbuttoned, your shoe untied, and every thing about you demonstrating a careless desolation.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Horatio:] [...] they say, you spirits oft walk in death [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] for thy dowry: be thou as chaste as ice, as pure as snow, thou shalt not escape calumny.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Marcellus:] Tis gone.
We do it wrong, being so majestical,
To offer it the show of violence,
For it is as the air, invulnerable,
And our vain blows malicious mockery.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: (Enter Iacomo unbraced and careless dressed).

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lampatho Doria:] Now by the front of Jove methinks her eye
Shoots more spirit in me, O beauty feminine!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Lupus:] Of strenuous vengeance to clutch the fist.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: True-Penny

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Camillo and Hippolito are young Venetian noblemen, just returned from the wars; Camillo brings with him a captured French gentleman named Fontinelle. Camillo turns his prisoner over to Hippolito's sister Violetta for safekeeping. Violetta is the object of Camillo's affections; but Fontinelle and Violetta fall in love. Learning of this unwelcome development, Camillo and Hippolito try to tempt Fontinelle to infidelity by sending his portrait to the courtesan Imperia, hoping to interest her in the Frenchman. The ploy fails (at first), and Camillio has Fontinelle thrown into prison. But Fontinelle and Violetta are secretly married. In the last act, however, the Venetians' plotting bears fruit: Fontinelle falls for Imperia, and Violetta has to resort to the standard Elizabethan bed trick

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Fool:] So I do, madonna. But to read his right wits is to read thus. Therefore, perpend, my princess, and give ear.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Olivia:] Have you not set mine honor at the stake [...]?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: (Enter Tucca, his boy after him with two pictures under his cloak, and a wreath of nettles: Horace and Bubo pulled in by th'horns bound both like Satyrs, Sir Adam following, Mistress Miniver with him, wearing Tucca's chain).

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Old Arthur:] [...] And doest thou use me thus? thou art a knave.
[Old Luke:] A knave, I marry, and an arrant knave:
And sirrah, by old M. Arthur's leave,
Though I be weak and old, I'll prove thee one.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Brabo:] When he comes next turne him into the streets,
Now come lets dance the shaking of the sheets.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Anselme:] Mistress God save you.
[Fulller:] What a block is that
To say God save you, is the fellow mad,
Once to name God in his ungodly suit?
[Mistress Arthur:] You are welcome sir. Come you to speak with me,
Or with my husband, pray you what's your will?
[Fuller:] She answers to the purpose, what's your will?
O zounds that I were there to answer her.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Andrew:] Nay, let him alone. I'll go another way to work with him. I'll have an action of battery against him, if there be any law in Illyria. Though I struck him first, yet it's no matter for that.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: For, would you not (in good sooth) imagine us all to be out of our wits: if you could make us believe, that the master devil himself with all his adherents were able to make a thing essentially existing in nature, either to be or not to be, when it pleases himself?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Prologue:] And hither am I come,
A prologue armed, but not in confidence
Of author's pen or actor’s voice, but suited
In like conditions as our argument,
To tell you, fair beholders, that our play
Leaps o'er the vaunt and firstlings of those broils,
Beginning in the middle, starting thence away
To what may be digested in a play.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Guildford:] Peace rest his soul, his sins be buried in his grave,
And not remembered in his Epitaph [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Achilles:] [...] see my reputation is at stake;
My fame is shrewdly gored.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Diomedes:] She's bitter to her country. Hear me, Paris:
For every false drop in her bawdy veins
A Grecian’s life hath sunk; for every scruple
Of her contaminated carrion weight
A Trojan hath been slain. Since she could speak,
She hath not given so many good words breath
As for her Greeks and Trojans suffered death.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Diomedes:] Thou dost miscall retire.
I do not fly, but advantageous care
Withdrew me from the odds of multitude.
Have at thee!
Have at thee, Hector.

[Achilles:] Now do I see thee. Ha! Have at thee, Hector!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Juggler:] [...] I'll show you a trick of the twelves, and turn him over the thumbs with a trice.
I'll make him fly swifter than meditation.
I'll show you as many toys as there be minutes in a month, and as many tricks as there be motes in the sun.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: How a man may chuse a good wife from a bad. A pleasant conceited Comedie, Wherein is shewed how a man may chuse a good Wife from a bad.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Northumberland:] Set forward then. (A dead march, and pass round the stage, and Guilford speaks).
The Tower will be a place of ample state,
Some lodgings in it, will like dead men's souls,
Remember us of frailty.
[Guilford:] We are led with pomp to prison,
O prophetic soul.
Lo we ascend into our chairs of State,
Like funeral Coffins, in some funeral
Pomp descending to their graves. But we must on.
How can we fare well, to keep our Court:
Where Prisoners keep their cave?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Troilus:] O beauty, where is thy faith?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [An axiom is a] Sentence, pronouncing a thing to be, or not to be.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lelia:] Father did you send for me?
[Gripe:] I wench I did, come hither Lelia, give me thy hand.
Mr. Churms , I pray you bear witness,
I here give Lelia to P. Ploddall.
(She plucks away her hand.)
How now?
[Nurse:] She'll none she thanks you Sir.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hector:] Now, youthful Troilus, do not these high strains
Of divination in our sister work
Some touches of remorse? Or is your blood
So madly hot that no discourse of reason
 Nor fear of bad success in a bad cause
Can qualify the same?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[...] when that fell arrest
Without all bail shall carry me away [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Aurelia:] Dri'd biscuit! look where the base wretch comes.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Duke as Friar:] [...] Thy best of rest is sleep,
 And that thou oft provok'st, yet grossly fear'st
Thy death, which is no more.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Pietro:] <span class="quote">Sad souls may well change place, but not change grief.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
If this be error, and upon me proved
I never writ, nor no man ever loved.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lucio:] [...] a man whose blood
Is very snow-broth [...]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Mendoza:] [...] oiled hinges, and all the tongue-tied lascivious witness of great creatures' wantonness [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Malevole:] Give place. Illo, ho, ho, ho, art there old truepenny? (Exit Celso) Where hast thou spent thy self this morning? I see flattery in thine eyes, and damnation in thy soul. Ha thou huge rascal!
[Mendoza:] Thou art very merry.
[Malevole:] As a scholar futuens gratis: How doth the devil go with thee now?
[Mendoza:] Malevole, thou art an arrant knave.
[Malevole:] Who I, I have been a Sergeant man.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Mendoza:] O! how full of ravishing attraction is your pretty, petulant, languishing, lasciviously-composed countenance these amorous smiles, those soul-warming sparkling glances, ardent as those flames that sing'd the world by heedless Phaeton; in body how delicate, in soul how witty, in discourse how pregnant, in life how wary, in favours how iuditious, in day how sociable, and in night how?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Francis:] Some music there, none lead the Bride a dance?
[Charles:] Yes, would she dance the shaking of the sheets? But that's the dance her Husband means to lead her?
[Wendoll:] That's not the dance that every man must dance According to the Ballad.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
To quench his thirst:
Runs to his Ink-pot, drinks, then stops the hole,
And thus grows madder, then he was at first.
Tasso, he finds, by that of Hamlet, thinks
Terms him a mad-man that of his Inkhorn drinks.
Calls players fools, the fool he judgeth wisest,
Will learn them Action out of Chaucer's Pander.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Lorenzo:] <span class="quote">Such a size of humanity now, and brain enough in it, it is not in the strength of a woman to withstand; well she may hold out a parley or two, for 'tis a weak fort that obeys at the first or second summons, if she resist the third she is discharg'd, though she yield in future: for then it appears it was no fault of hers: but the man that would take no denial. What rests now? means for access: True. O an honest Bawd were worth gold now.</spanA

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: The Honest Whore

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Musician:] Whereby hangs a tale, sir?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King Philip:] It likes us well, but royal Queen we want
One Lady at this high solemnity:
We have a Sister call'd Elixabeth,
Whose virtues and endowments of the mind
Hath fil'd the ears of Spain.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: He fell in love with another, A wedded Lady: Then with a fourth [...]. And so far was he imparadized in her beauty (she not recomforting him) that he fell from Love to passion, so to distraction, then to admiration, & contemplation: lately, to madness [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Brabantio:] I had rather to adopt a child than get it.
Come hither, Moor.
I here do give thee that with all my heart
Which, but thou hast already, with all my heart
I would keep from thee. - For your sake, jewel,
I am glad at soul I have no other child,
For thy escape would teach me tyranny,
To hang clogs on them.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Henry Condell:] I beseech you sir be covered.
 [Sly:] No in good faith for mine ease, look you my hat's the handle to this fan [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Malheureux:] I, a man of snow
Now shame forsake me whether am I fallen!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Franceschina:] I do not love Freevill.
[Malheureux:] But what vow, what vow?
[Franceschina:] So long as Freevill lives, I must not love.
[Malheureux:] Then he –
[Franceschina:] Must -
[Malheureux:] Die!
[Franceschina:] Ay. - No, there is no such vehemence in your affects.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Æmilia:] O Sir, you men have not devices with ladders of ropes to scale such walls at your pleasure, and abuse us poor wenches.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Rerrage:] Andrew Lethe is well whipped in't, his name stands in a white sheet here, and does penance for him.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Gozlin:] Consort with a pox? Cannot the shaking of the sheets be danc'd without your Town piping?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lodovico:] O thou Othello, that wert once so good,
Fall’n in the practice of a damnèd slave,
What shall be said to thee?
[Othello:] Why, anything. An honorable murderer, if you will […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Iago:] Now, whether he kill Cassio,
Or Cassio him, or each do kill the other,
Every way makes my gain.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Othello:] And O you mortal engines, whose rude throats
Th' immortal Jove’s dread clamors counterfeit,
Farewell!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Iago:] [...] Or else the devil will make a grandsire of you.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Iago:] Help, masters! - Here's a goodly watch indeed! (A bell is rung)
Who's that which rings the bell? Diablo, ho!
The town will rise. God's will, lieutenant, hold!
You will be shamed forever.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Lucre:] [...] here's none but friends [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Nuntio:] She told her that her death was too too good,
And that already she had lived too long.
 She said she shamed to have a part in blood
Of her that did the princely Herod wrong.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Asdrubal:] Through rotten'st dung best plants both sprout and live by blood vines grow.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Renaldo:] [...] My Prince and brother, let my blood and love
challenge the freedom of one question [...].
[Ferrara explains why he wants to leave]
[Renaldo:] I commend all to your wisdom, and yours to the wisest.
[...] (exit).
[Hercules, disguised Duke Ferrara:] And now thou Ceremonious sovereignty
Ye proud severer statefull Complements
The secret arts of Rule, I put you off [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Zuccone:] Nay, I will embrace, nay I will embrace a Jakes-farmer after eleven o' clock at night, I will stand bare, and give wall to a Bellows-mender, pawn my Lordship, sell my foot-cloth, but I will be revenged, does she think she has married an Ass?
[Hercules:] A Fool?
[Zuccone:] A Coxcomb?
[Hercules:] A Ninnyhammer?
[Zuccone:] A Woodcock?
[Hercules:] A Calf?
[Zuccone:] No, she shall find that I ha' eyes.
[Hercules:] And brain.
[Zuccone:] And nose.
[Hercules:] And Forehead.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Sophonisba:] It is but sleepy Opium he hath drunk [...]
[They lay Vangue in Syphax bed and draw the curtains]
There lie Syphax bride, a naked man is soon undressed;
There bide dishonoured passion.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Zoya:] Well, upon your apparent repentance, that all modest spectators may witness, I have for a short time only thus feignedly hated you, that you might ever after truely love me, upon these cautions I reaccept you: first you shall vow.
[Zuccone:] I do vow, as heaven bless me, I will do.
[Zoya:] What?
[Zuccone:] Whate'er it be, say on I beseech you.
[Zoya:] You shall vow.
[Zuccone:] Yes.
[Zoya:] That you shall never.
[Zuccone:] Never.
[Zoya:] Feign love to my waiting woman or chamber maid.
[Zuccone:] No.
[Zoya:] Never promise them such a farm to their marriage.
[Zuccone:] No.
[Zoya:] If she'll discover but whom I affect.
[Zuccone:] Never. [Zoya:] Or if they know none that they'll but take a false oath; I do, only to be rid of me.
[Zuccone:] I swear I will not, I will not only not counterfeit love your women, but I will truely hate them an't be possible, so far from maintaining them that I will beggar them, I will never pick their trunks for letters, search their pockets, ruffle their bosoms, or tear their foul smocks never, never.
[Zoya:] That if I chance to have a humour to be in a mask, you shall not grow Jealous.
[Zuccone:] Never.
[Zoya:] Or grudge at the expense.
[Zuccone:] Never, I will eat mine own arms first.
[Zoya:] That you shall not, search if my chamber door hinges be oiled to avoid creaking.
[Zuccone:] As I am a sensible creature-
[Zoya:] Nor ever suspect the reason why my bed-chamber floor is double matted.
[Zuccone:] Not as I have blood in me.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Who would endure the mocks and scorns of the world [...] unless they hoped, that after the vessel of their bodies were seasoned in the womb of the earth, they should arrive at that blessed undiscovered country, where is no mediocrity of joy, no end of pleasure.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hercules, Duke of Ferrara:] Plots ha you laid? Inductions, dangerous.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: (Orlando in disguise enters the service of his daughters in order to preserve them from shame and scandal)

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Maybery:] Of what rank was she I beseech you.
[Featherstone:] Upon your promise of secrecy.
[Bellamont:] You shall close it up like treasure of your own, and yourself shall keep the key of it.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Cordelia:] Alack, 'tis he! Why, he was met even now
As mad as the vexed sea, singing aloud,
Crowned with rank fumiter and furrow-weeds,
With hardocks, hemlock, nettles, cuckooflowers,
Darnel, and all the idle weeds that grow
In our sustaining corn.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Dialogue between Hamlet and the ghost

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Duchess:] Was't ever known stepduchess was so mild
And calm as I? Some now would plot his death,
With easy doctors, those loose-living men,
And make His withered Grace fall to his grave
And keep church better.
Some second wife would do this, and dispatch
Her double loathèd lord at meat and sleep.
Indeed, 'tis true an old man's twice a childe,
Mine cannot speak; one of his single words,
Would quite have freed my youngest dearest son
From death or durance, and have made him walk
With a bold foote vpon the thorny law,
Whose prickles should bow under him, but 'tis not,
And therefore wedlock faith shall be forgot,
I'll kill him in his forehead, hate there feed,
That wound is deepest though it neuer bleed.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Duke of Millain]: How old are you?
[Lazarello]: Full eight and twenty several Almanacks
Hath been compiled, all for several years
Since first I drew this breath; four apprenticeships
Have I most truly served in this world:
And eight and twenty times hath Phoebus Cart
Run out his yearly course since -
[Duke]: I understand you Sir.
[Lucio]: How like an ignorant Poet he talks.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Count]: I am glad to meet you here Sister.
[Oriana]: I thank you good Brother: and if you doubt of the cause of my coming I can Satisfy you.
[Count]: No faith, I dare trust thee, I do suspect thou art honest; for it is so rare a thing to be honest amongst you, that some one man in an age, may perhaps suspect some two women to be honest, but never believe it verily.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Lady Macbeth:] Here's the smell of the blood still. All the perfumes of Arabia will not sweeten this little hand. O, O, O!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
(Tactus, in a dark coloured Satin mantle over a pair of silk Baset, a Garland of Bays mixed with red and white Roses [...] etc.)
[Mendacio:] Now chaste Diana grant my nets to hold.
[Tactus:] The blasting Child-hood of the cheerful morn
Is almost grown a youth and over-climbs
Yonder gilt Eastern hills [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Macbeth:] The rest is labor which is not used for you.
I'll be myself the harbinger and make joyful
The hearing of my wife with your approach.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Macbeth:] [...] Will all great Neptune's ocean wash this blood
Clean from my hand? No, this my hand will rather
The multitudinous seas incarnadine,
Making the green one red.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Duke:] Weightier far:
You are my friends and you shall have the cause:
I break my sleeps thus soon to see a wench.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Frip:] [...] here's none but friends [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Maria:] O that this flesh could like swift-moving thoughts transfer itself,
From place to place, unseen and undissolved.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Glister:] What else, sir? I have reason.
 [Dryfat:] I know it well, I take you for no beast.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Gerardine:] This is the abstract of the spacious world.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Maria:] Go fetch my ladder of Ropes, Leander's come.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Graccus:] Excellent, for now must he needs fall into the Constable's hands: and if he have any grace, t'will appear in his face, when he shall be carried through the street in a white sheet t'will be a good penance for his fault.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Gudgin:] Ere long he will take up his station at a Stationers, where we shall see him do penance in a Sheet at least.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Flamineo:] Let me see, it is more than time that I commit this divine pill to his hopeful working: least my staff be out of the rest when my adversary is in the carrier.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [First Servingman:] […] Peace is […] a getter of more bastard children than war is a destroyer of men.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Martius:] When drums and trumpets shall I' th' field prove flatterers […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: By these instances, and many more that might be alleged to this purpose, it is apparant, upon how weake and unstable grounds the Case-divinity of the Popish Church standeth, and how indirect a course they take, for the resolution and direction of the troubled Conscience.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Sir Oliver:] God morrow Bride, fresh, fresh, as the month of May [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Adriana:] A pretty knave, in faith come home to night,
Shalt have a posset and candied Eringoes,
A bed if need be to, I love a life,

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Frances:] You know sir,
I did enjoy a quiet country life,
Spotless and free, till you corrupted me,
And brought me to the Court, I never knew,
What sleeking, glazing, or what pressing meant,
Till you preferred me to your Aunt the Lady,
I knew no Ivory teeth, no caps of hair,
No Mercury water, fucas, or perfumes,
To helpe a Lady's breath, untill your Aunt,
Learnt me the common trick.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[William Small-shanks:] [...] the widow and myself,
Will scamble out the shaking of the sheets,
Without your music, we have no need of fiddlers,
To our dancing, foot have you no manners,
Cannot a man take his natural rest.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [A Tinker (with a cord):] 'Tis bitter cold; a plague upon these Rogues, how wary they are grown? not a door open now, but double bard, not a window, but up with a case of wood like a spice box, and their locks unpickable, the very smiths that were half venturers, drink penitent single Ale, this is the Iron age, the Ballad sings of; well I shall meet with some of our loose Linen yet, good fellows must not starve; here's he shall show you God a mighty's dog bolts, if this hold.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Justice:] There hangs a tale.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Widow:] Nay prithee tell the cause, come here's none but friends.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
He's gone! That lightning that a while doth strike
Our eyes with amaz'd greatness, and on a sudden
Leaves us in prison'd darkness.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Subtle:] She's a rare wife believe it, Sir, were all such,
We never should have false inheritors.
[Husband:] Pish friend, there is not woman in the world
Can hold out in the end, if youth, shape, wit,
Met in one subject, do assault her aptly [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Husband:] [...] you must woo discretely; first observe
The disposition of her you attempt,
If she be sprightly and heroical,
Possess her that you are valiant, and have spirit,
Talk nothing but of beating every man
That is your hindrance, though you do not do it,
Or dare not, 'tis no matter.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Truewit:] 'Tis true. No more then all birds, or all fishes. If you appear learned to an ignorant wench, or jocund to a sad, or witty to a foolish, why she presently begins to mistrust herself. You must approach them i'their own height, their own line: for the contrary makes many that fear to commit themselves to noble and worthy fellows, run into the embraces of a rascal. If she love wit, give verses, though you borrow 'em of a friend, or buy 'em, to have good. If valour, talk of your sword, and be frequent in the mention of quarrels, though you be staunch in fighting. If activity, be seen o' your barbary often, or leaping over stools, for the credit of your back. If she love good clothes or dressing, have your learned counsel about you every morning, your French taylor, barber, linnener et cetera. Let your powder, your glass, and your comb be your dearest acquaintance. Take more care for the ornament of your head than the safety: and wish the common-wealth rather troubled, than a hair about you. That will take her. Then if she be covetous and craving, do you promise anything, and perform sparingly: so shall you keep her in appetite still. Seem as you would give, but be like a barren field that yields little, or unlucky dice to foolish and hoping gamesters. Let your gifts be slight and dainty, rather then precious. Let cunning be above cost. Give cherries at time of yeare, or apricots; and say they were sent you out o' the country, though you bought 'em in Cheapside . Admire her tears; like her in all fashions; compare her in every habit to some deity; invent excellent dreams to flatter her, and riddles, or, if she bee a great one, performe always the second parts to her: like what she likes, praise whom she praises, and fail not to make the household and servants yours, yea the whole family, and salute 'em by their names: ('tis but light cost if you can purchase 'em so) and make her physician your pensioner, and her chief woman. Nor will it be out of your gain to make love to her too, so she follow, not usher, her ladies' pleasure. All blabbing is taken away, when she comes to be a part of the crime.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Roger:] Have patience Sir, untill our fellow Nicholas be deceased, that is, asleep: for so the word is taken; to sleep to die, to die to sleep: a very Figure Sir.
[Welford:] Cannot you cast another for the Gentlewoman?
[Roger:] Not till the man be in his bed, his grave; his grave his bed; the very same again Sir.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Drawer:] [...] I have been at Bess Turnup's and she swears all the Gentlewomen went to see a Play at the Fortune, and are not come in yet, and she believes they sup with Players.
[Tear-Chops:] Damn me, we must kill all those rogues, we shall never keep a whore honest for them.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [D'Amville:] With an amazement behold thine error and be planet struck.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Isabella:] Here is a man of a most mild aspect,
Temperate, effeminate, and worthy love,
One that with burning ardor hath pursued me:
A donative he hath of every God;
Apollo gave him locks, Jove his high front,
 The God of Eloquence his flowing speech,
The feminine Deities strewed all their bounties
And beauty on his face: that eye was Juno's,
Those lips were his that won the golden Ball,
That virgin-blush Diana's: here they meet,
As in a sacred Synod.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Jailer:] A heavy reckoning for you, sir. But the comfort is, you shall be called to no more payments, fear no more tavern bills, which are often the sadness of parting as the procuring of mirth. You come in faint for want of meat, depart reeling with too much drink; sorry that you have paid too much, and sorry that you are paid too much; purse and brain both empty; the brain the heavier for being too light; the purse too light, being drawn of heaviness.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Savill, the Steward:] Now must I hang myself, my friends will look for't.
Eating and sleeping, I do despise you both now:
I will run mad first, and if that get not pity,
I'll drown myself, to a most dismal ditty.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Isabella:] Good my Lord, be my expositer [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Roberto:] See how yond Star like beauty in a cloud,
Illumines darkness, and beguiles the Moon
Of all her glory in the firmament.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Roberto: I ne'er was so kissed, leave thus to please,
Flames into flames, seas thou pour'st into seas.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Mendosa:] Or what say you to a fine scaling Ladder of ropes?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Mendosa:] Yet she a fresh Bride as the month of May.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Roberto:] Angels of grace, Amen, Amen, say to't.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Levidulcia:] [...] The sea wants water enough to wash away [...]
The foulness of my name.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Claridiana:] Candied Eringoes, I beseech thee.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Abigail:] Thais; you're an early riser. I have that to show will make your hair stand an-end.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Don Sago:] Although Neptolis cold, the waves of all the northern sea,
Should flow forever, through these guilty hands,
Yet the sanguinolent stain would extant be.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Abigail:] [...] here's a white sheet, that your husband has promised me to do penance in: you must not think to dance the shaking of the sheets alone [...]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Even as a head-strong courser bears away,
His rider vainly striving him to stay.
Or as a sudden gale thrusts into sea,
The heaven-touching bark now near the lea.
So wavering Cupid brings me back amain,
And purple love resumes his darts again.
Here of themselves thy shafts come, as if shot;
Better then I their quiver knows them not.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Claridiana:] The staff is now advancing for the rest,
and when I tilt; Rogero aware thy crest.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: A Christian turn'd Turke

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: O love too sweet, in the digestion sour.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: (He exits, pursued by a bear.)

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Francisco:] As in cold countries husbandmen plant vines,
And with warm blood manure them, even so
One summer she will bear unsavoury fruit

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[The Moore:] Look you; who are yonder.
[Cornelia:] O reach me the flowers.
[The Moore:] Her Ladyships foolish.
[Woman:] Alas! her grief
Hath turn'd her child again.
[Cornelia:] You're very welcome.
There's Rosemary for you, and Rue for you, (to Flamineo).
Hearts-ease for you. I pray make much of it.
I have left more for myself. [...]
Call for the Robin-Red-brest and the wren,
Since o'er shady groves they hover, (Cornelia doth this in several forms of distraction)
And with leaves and flowers do cover
The friendless bodies of unburied men.
Call unto his funeral Dole
The Ant, the field-mouse, and the mole
To rear him hillocks, that shall keep him warm,
And (when gay tombs are rob'd) sustain no harm,
But keep the wolf far thence: that's foe to men,
For with his nails he'll dig them up again.
They would not bury him 'cause he died in a quarrel
But I have an answer for them.
Let holy Church receive him duly
Since he payed the Church tithes truly.
His wealth is sum'd, and this is all his store:
This poor men get; and great men get no more.
Now the wares are gone, we may shut up shop.
Bless you all good people.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Flamineo:] Or cuckolds, for your cuckold is your most terrible tickler of lechery. Whore-masters would serve, for none are judges at tilting, but those that have been old Tilters.

[Lawer:] Oh, my sprightly Frenchman. do you know him? He's an admirable Tilter.
[Flamineo:] I saw him at last Tilting, he showed like a pewter candlestick fashioned like a man in armour, holding a Tilting staff in his hand, little bigger than a candle of twelve i'th pound.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Dorothea:] [...] she had more
need of Mace-ale, and Rhenish-wine Candles, heaven knows,
than your aged discipline.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Dorigen:] Perish, Martius, then;
for I here vow unto the gods, These rocks,
these rocks we see so fix'd, shall be removed,
made champion field, ere I so impious prove,
to stain my Lord's bed with adulterous love.
[...]
[Martius:] These peasants mock me sure, Valerius,
forgive my dotage, see my ashes urn'd, and tell fair Dorigen
(she that but now left me with this harsh vow,
Sooner these rocks should be remov'd, than she would yield) that I
was yet so loving, on her gift to die.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Arcite:] [...] And a broad beech - and thereby hangs a tale. Heigh ho!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Officer one:] The strenuous fist of vengeance now is clutched; therefore fear nothing.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: There are of opinion, that there is, in marriage, an inevitable destiny, an inevitable destiny, not to be avoided, which is either to be actaeoned, or not to be; if it be not, as is the opinion of some damned in the error of predestination, then let him take a house in Fleet-street, divide it like an inn, into as many several lodgings as rooms; [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Russell:] Come, tell truth 'twixt ourselves, here's none but friends.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Wife:] Nay, 'tis no matter, as he likes this, let him dance the shaking of the sheets another time.
[...] [Shoemaker:] Hoyda, and is this the shaking of the sheets you talk of, good wife Snipper Snapper [...]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Then bid the wanton Lady tread,
Amid these mazes of the dead.
And these truly understood,
More shall cool and quench the blood
Then her many sports aday,
And her nighty wanton play,
Bid her paint till day of doom,
To this favour she must come [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Strophius:]: What temper's grown on the distracted Queen!
Hath grief conceiv'd for her late husband's death,
Brought her so far, she hath forgot herself?
[Orestes:] No Uncle, no, by heaven, I do suspect,
O, my prophetic soul divines much ill:
Well, I will fly, but hear this stratagem,
It shall be rumor'd i'th ear o'th Court
I was found dead, I'll put a new shape on,
And live alone, to hear how things go here.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Simon:] Now sirs, are you comedians?
[Second Cheater:] We are anything sir: comedians, tragedians, tragicomedians, comi-tragedians, pastoralists, humorists, clownists and satirists. We have'em, sir, from the smile to the laugh, from the laugh to the handkerchief.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Sapritius:] Wouldst thou recouer?
[Antoninus:] Would I liue in blisse?
[Sapritius:] And doe thine eyes shoote daggers at that man
That brings thee health? [Antoninus:] It is not in the world?
[Sapritius:] Ist heere? [Antoninus:] Oh Treasure, by enchantment lock'd
In Caues as deepe as hell, am I as neere?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
For Princes are the glass, the school, the brook,
Where subjects' eyes do learn, do read, do look.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Epilogue:] He'll stand no shock of censure; the Play's good,
He says he knows it (if well understood.)

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Master:] See, provoking dishes, candied Eringoes, And Potatoes.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Moll:] [...] my mind gives me, thee and I shall dance the shaking of the sheets together.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Cleremond:] [...] Look not on me
As I am Cleremond: I have parted with
The essence that was his, and entertained
The soul of some fierce tigress, or a wolf
New-hanged for human slaughter.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Rufaldo:] I am sure, love kept me waking, and the expectation of this my wedding day did so caper in my brains, I thought of nothing but dancing the shaking of the sheets with my sweet-heart.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Malefort:] The pleurisy of goodness is thy ill,
Thy virtues vices, and thy humble lowness
Far worse than stubborn sullenness, and pride,
Thy looks that ravish all beholders else
As killing as the Basilisks, their tears
Expressed in sorrow for thee much I suffer,
A glorious insultation, and no sign
Of pity in thee, and to hear thee speak
In thy defence, though but in silent action,
Would make the hurt already deeply festered
Incurable [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Old Bateman:] [...] we will sit, and write the tragedy
Of our poor Children; I'll ha't so set down
As not one eye that views it, but shall weep,
Not any ear but sadly shall relent:
For never was a story of more ruth
Then this of him, and her, yet nought but truth.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Menaphon:] Such cure as sick men find in changing beds,
I found in change of airs; the fancy flatter'd
My hopes with ease, as theirs do, but the grief
Is still the same.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Breines:] [...] now I do long to know what pitiful lover for it can be no other, is doing penance in that white sheet already, Mistris Sensible hark yee; whence came that letter?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Their Parents jarr'd, and never could agree,
Till both of them were drowned in misery.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Orgilus:] So much out of self-unworthiness His fears transport him; not that he finds cause in her obedience, but his own distrust.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Orgilus:] Souls sunk in sorrows never are without'em;
They change fresh airs, but bear their griefs about'em.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Eleazer:] To be, or not to be, ay there's the doubt,
For to be Sovereign by unlawful means,
Is but to be a slave to base desire,
And where's my honour then? What a strange buzzing of ambition
Pursues my thirsty soul?
O Eleazer! can thy traitor breast
Give harbour to a thought of Parricide?
It is thy father, O the sacred tie
Of filial duty, how that awful name
Affrighteth all my faculties with fear -
With fear? - of what? - with foolery by heaven;
If there be ought within this awful name
That can extort obedience from a son.
'Tis but the rotten Carcass, there's the thing
That for to please itself begets another,
So does a beast, and yet 'twixt them we see
An equal freedom of society:
As for the nobler part of man we know
That's of a higher birth, if it be so,
Thus low my knee shall bend, but thou my heart (Bends his knee)
Scorn to obey, remember where thou art:
I am resolv'd, the times are bloody, and the people's hearts
I hear, are bent on me: Jehochanan the man
that I must fairly close with all, this done,
We shall be strong for opposition.
Soft, here he comes (Enter Jehochanan).

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Tip:] I'll set him up, then. Art thou the Dominus?
Host:] Fac-totum here, Sir.
[Tip:] Host real o'the house? and Cap of Maintenance?
[Host:] The Lord o'the light Heart, Sir, Cap a pie;
VVhere of the Feather is the Emblem, Colonel,
Put up, with the Ace of Hearts!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [...] in as much as they are said to be possible to be or not to be, this is not from the decree of God but rather from the nature of God, as all necessary truths are derived therefrom. Neither is it in the power of God to make that the works of men and Angels should not be possible to be or not to be. But if the possibility were the object of Gods decree, it might be otherwise. For Gods decree passeth forely upon every thing whereupon it passeth, so that if he decree them to be possible, he might have decreed them not to be possible. [...] Things cannot be known to be future until they are future; (for to apprehend or conceive things to be future, when they are not future, is not to know, but to err,) but contingent things, and only possible to be or not to be, do not become future till the determination of Gods will hath made them future. [...] For to be contingent is to be indifferent to be or not to be. But that which is, neither is nor possibly can be indifferent to be or not to be. Yet herehence it followeth not, that it came to pass necessarily there is no colour for any such inference. For what? doth nothing come to pass but necessarily? but whether it comes to pass necessarily or contingently, being once come to pass the contingency of it is at an end, and past irrecoverably. For it is no longer indifferent to be or not to be. [...] For to be contingent is to be indifferent to be or not to be. But that which is, neither is nor possibly can be indifferent to be or not to be.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Sexton]:This was the prime Madam in Thebes, the general Mistress, the only adored beauty. Little would you think there were a couple of stars in these two augur-holes: or that this pit had been arch'd over with a handsome nose, that had been at the charges to maintain half a dozen of several silver arches to uphold the bridge. It had been a mighty favour once, to have kiss'd these lips that grin so. This mouth out of all the Madams boxes cannot now be furnished with a set of teeth. She was the coyest overcurious dame in all the city: her chambermaids misplacing of a hair, was as much as her place came to.- Oh! if that Lady now could but behold this physiognomy of hers in a looking-glass, what a monster would she imagine her self! Will all her perukes, tyres and dresses, with her chargeable teeth, with her cerise and pomatum, and the benefit of her painter and doctor, make this idol up again?
Paint Ladies while you live, and plaister fair,
But when the house is fallne 'tis past repair.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Souls that will mount, gain a Celestial Crown,
Must pray with ardency, look up, not down [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Goldwire:] The curtains drawn, my Fidlers playing all night The shaking of the sheets, which I have danc'd Again, and again with my Cockatrice.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clotair:] […] yet we may sit
And gaze upon each other, tell sad tales
Of ruin'd princes, wrong'd virginity […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clotair:] Your broken pledge of faith; and with this kiss,
The last that ever Clovis must print here:
Unkiss the kiss that seal'd it on thy lips.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[2nd Soldier:] [...] A bounding Courser, who is therefore proud
To be so back'd, as knowing whom he bears [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Dumaine:] This bastard-getting peace unspirits me [...]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Dumaine:] The Drums and Trumpets are turn'd flatterers […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Clothair:] [...] Let me bedew thy Herse with pious tears,
Balm to wounds, repenting ones [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Clothair:] Call me an honourable murderer.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Eunuch:] Clovis enraged perhaps will kill the king
or by the king will perish; if both fall,
Or either, both ways make for me.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Eunuch:] They had the Devil to their Grand-father.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Eunuch:] Ring out the alarm Bell. (Rings the bell) The Princes here will murder one another. For shame for shame forbear.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Spirit:] [...] Amaz'd I stood, harrow'd with grief and fear,
And O poor hapless Nightingale thought I,
How sweet thou sing'st, how near the deadly snare!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lady:] Enough, good friend no more.
had a rude Scythian ignorant of tears
unless the wind enforce them from his eyes,
heard this relation sure he would have wept,
and yet I cannot I have lost all sense
of pity, with my womanhood, and now
that once essential Mistress of my soul
warm charity, no more inflames my breast
then does the glowworm's uneffectual fire
the haed that touches it good sir desist
the aggravation of your sad report
I've too much grief already.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Bravo:] I am, sweet creature, a kinde of lawless Justicer, or usurping Martialist of authority, that will kill any man with my safety.
[Lucretia:] And you purpose the death of this Gentleman?
[Bravo:] I will do any thing for hire.
[Lucretia:] Have you no conscience?
[Bravo:] Conscience! I know what it is: why should any man live, and I want money?
[Lucretia:] Have you no regard then of innocence?
[Bravo:] 'Tis crime enough, he has a life.
[Lucretia:] How long have you been vers'd in this trade?
 [Bravo:] 'Tis my vocation.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Tell me, (oh thou of Mankind most accursed)
Whether to be, or not to be, was first?
Whether to understand, or not to know?
To reason, or not reason? (well bee't so,
I make that proposition: all agree,
That our Not being, was before To be.
For we that are now, were not in Times past:
Our parents too, ev'n when our moulds were cast,
Had their progenitors: their fathers, theirs:
So to the first. By which it plain appears,
And by this demonstration 't is most clear,
That all of us were not, before we were.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Flavio:] Distrust of what they call their own, or jealousy
[…] without control, begets a self unworthiness;
For which fear, or what is worst desire […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King:] Enough of that, thou dost but gently chide me for a fault, that I will mend; for I have been too poor, and low in my rewards unto thy virtue: but to our business; the question is, whether we shall rely upon our Guards again?
[Ziriff:] By no means Sir: hope on his future fortunes, or their Love unto his person, has so sicklied o'er their resolutions, that we must not trust them.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Epilogue:] Plays are like Feasts, and every Act should bee
Another Course, and still variety:
But in good faith provision of wit
Is grown of late so difficult to get,
That do we what we can, we are not able,
Without cold meats to furnish out the Table.
Who knows but it was needless too? may be
'Twas here, as in the Coach-man's trade, and he
That turns in the least compass, shows most Art:
How ere, the Poet hopes (Sir) for his part,
You'll like not those so much, who show their skill
In entertainment, as who show their will.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Aglaura:] Antiques and strange mishaps,
such as the Porter to my Soul, mine Eye,
was ne'er acquainted with, Fancy lets in,
like a distracted multitude, by some strange accident
piec'd together, fear now afresh comes on,
and charges Love to home.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lucio:] It is not wisdom to proclaim our charge,
Though I could be content to be a Lord,
I am not over hearty, thieves are thieves,
And life is precious, prithee let's make haste.
[Piperollo:] Illo ho ho,
Think upon your honour, are there no Gentlemen?
No wanting Gentlemen that know how to spend
A quantity of Gold?
There is no thief in Nature.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: I had rather stand the shock of a Basilisk than in the fury of a merciless pen. It is not mere zeal to Learning, or Devotion to the Muses, that wiser Princes Patron the Arts, and carry an indulgent aspect unto Scholars; but a desire to have their names eternized by the memory of their writings, and a fear of the revengeful pen of succeeding ages: for these are the men that, when they have played their parts, and had their exits, must step out and give the moral of their Scenes, and deliver unto Posterity an Inventory of their virtues and vices.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: The smattering I have of the Philosopher's stone (which is something more than the perfect exaltation of gold) hath taught me a great deal of Divinity, and instructed my belief, how that immortal spirit and incorruptible substance of my soul may lie obscure, and sleep a while within this house of flesh.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Those strange and mystical transmigrations that I have observed in Silkworms, turn'd my Philosophy into Divinity. There is in these works of nature, which seem to puzzle reason, something Divine; and hath more in it than [sic] the eye of a common spectator doth discover.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: If there be any among those common objects of hatred I do contemn and laugh at, it is that great enemy of reason, virtue, and religion, the multitude; that numerous piece of monstrosity, which, taken asunder seem men, and the reasonable creatures of God; but confused together, make but one great beast, & a monstrosity more prodigious than Hydra [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: I find my growing Judgement daily instructs me how to be better, but my untamed affections and confirmed vitiosity makes me daily do worse; I find in my confirmed age the same sins I discovered in my youth, I committed many then because I was a child, and because I commit them still I am yet an Infant. Therefore I perceive a man may be twice a child before the days of dotage, and stand in need of Aeson's bath before threescore.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: I cannot believe the story of the Italian; our bad wishes and malevolous desires proceed no further than this life; it is the Devil and the uncharitable votes of Hell, that desire our misery in the world to come.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Soldier:] From the Commanders, Col. Rainsborow, and Comissary Ireton, I have in trust to let you know, some minutes hence you are to die. (Exit).
[Sir Charles:] Oh perjur'd Miscreants! is this your mercy ? this my prophetic Soul still whisper'd to me; I knew they in our bloods would bathe their guilt, and sacrifice our lives to their God Treason, these Victims befit Molech , not Messiah , whom these professed Saints, but real Devils, seem to make the umpire of their deeds.

Angry Rhamnusia , though we fall to dust,
Punish these Traytors, for their acts unjust.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Duke Gondibert:] Nor would I by a total silence yield
My honour ta'ne, though I were Pris'ner made;
Least you should think we may be justly kill'd,
And sacred justice by mistake invade.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Duke:] [...] Cease his destroying dart! and in its room
Place thine of Gold, then wound him with his own,
Ev'n to destruction! so shalt thou prove
A glorious victor, I, she, live and love.
[Honorio:] It is, as my prophetic soul inform'd me,
And now for my discovery (to him Hono)
[Duke:] How dar'st thou interrupt our privacy?
Have we no power?
[Honorio:] But calm that stormy brow! your grace forthwith
Shall feel the ease I bring you.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Don Gerardo:] These Actions sure did seem a perfect madness.
[Servant:] It seem'd indeed a madness methodiz'd,
Like theirs who are Transported far with Passion.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lysimachus:] A voice! To whom should this address belong!
O Gods! There's Parisatis list'ning to the Song!
Ephestion too! O my prophetique Soul!
What shall I do to keep my senses whole!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Sir Noble Clumsy:] Why, you sweet perfum'd Jessamine knaves! you Rogues in Buckram! were there a Dozen of ouy, I'd beat you out of your artificial Sweetness into your own natural Rankness.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lyonel:] [...] (Sings) There's nothing so fatal as Woman,
To hurry a Man to his Grave,
You must think, you may plot,
You may sigh like a Sot:
She uses you more like a Slave.
But a Bottle, altho' it be common,
The Cheats of the Fair will undo,
It will drive from your Head
The Delights of the Bed;
He that's drunk is not able to wooe.
(Exit Lyonel)
[Celia:] Method in Madness, Grace even in Distraction: I'll never leave him, 'till, by Art or Prayer, I have restor'd his Senses to their Office.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Lyonel:] A Horse; a Horse; my Kingdom for a Horse: What's here, a Woman, charging at their Army's Head? then we are betray'd.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
O dastard Coward, Stutly cries,
Faint-hearted, Peasant Slave!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Mors omnibus communis

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Mare malorum
A sea of troubles
Kakôn thálassa, A sea of troubles. This is usually said of catastrophes which are boundless and manifold, because the sea is an infinite thing, or else because those who occupy themselves in it are subject to infinite hardships.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: machina mundi

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Gaudium Dolori junctum

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Felicitas multas habet amicos

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Summum jus, summa injuria.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Mnerum animus optimus

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: mala malis eveniunt

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Duos insequens lepores neutrum capit

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: A subdistinction or Comma, is a note of silence, or rather a place of breathing; as whereby the term of pronunciation, the sentence still remaining, is so suspended: as that that which followeth ought presently to succed.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[...] demum totius machina mundi
 Hoc stat, & hoc durat tot iam per saecula nexu.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: But the crowd of our nobility do not follow the precept (as to the value of writing), for they think it is a fine and becoming thing not to know how to form their letters. You would say their writing was the scratching of hens, and unless you were warned beforehand whose hand it was, you would never guess.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: The woman is a weak creature [...] She is the weaker vessel, of a frail heat, inconstant [...]. The woman is the more frail part [...]. The woman is a frail vessel.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Prologue] We search not Plutos pensive pit, nor taste of Limbo lake.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Rosemary is for remembrance,
between us day and night:
Wishing that I might always have,
you present in my sight.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [...] the brain as tender as a posset curd [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Tamburlaine:] For Tamburlaine, the scourge of God, must die.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Muly Mahamet:] And honor of undoubted victory,
Makes me exclaim upon this dastard flight.
Why, King Sebastian, wilt thou now forslow,
And let so great a glory slip thy hands?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Muly Mahamet:] A horse, a horse, villain, a horse
That I may take the river straight and fly.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Dido:] [...] Thy mother was no goddess, perjured man,
Nor Dardanus the author of thy stock;
But thou art sprung from Scythian Caucasus,
And tigers of Hercynia gave thee suck.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Suleiman:] Ah heavens that hitherto have smiled on me,
Why do you unkindly lower on Soliman?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Brusor:] [...] What say these prisoners? will they turn Turk, or not?
[Iuilo:] First Julio will die ten thousand deaths.
[Guelpio:] And Guelpio, rather than deny his Christ.
[Bruso:] Then stab the slaves, and send their souls to hell.
([Soldiers] stab Julio and Guelpio)
[Basilisco:] I turn, I turn; oh, save my life, I turn.
[Bruso:] Forbear to hurt him; when we land in Turkey,
He shall be circumcised and have his rites.
[Basilisco:] Think you I turn Turk for fear of servile death that's but a sport? I' faith, sir, no;
Tis for Perseda, whom I love so well
That I would follow her though she went to hell.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Presenter:] Sit down and see what heinous stratagems These damned wits contrive.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Presenter:] Till Nemesis high mistress of revenge, That with her scourge keeps all the world in awe, With thundering drums awakes the God of war

[Presenter:] And Nemesis with bloody whip in hand
thunders for vengeance on this negro Moor.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Muly Mahamet:] Be Pluto then in hell and bar the fiends,
Take Neptune's force to thee and calm the seas,
And execute Jove's justice on the world,
Convey Tamburlaine into our Africa here,
To chastise and to menace lawful kings,
Tamburlaine triumph not, for thou must die
As Philip did, Cæsar, and Cæsar's peers.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Muly Mahamet:] Restless, till I be safely set in shade
Of some unhaunted place, some blasted grove.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Bashaw:] As glorious as great Pompey in his pride.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Muly Mahamet:] Where art thou boy, where is Calipolis?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Muly Mahamet:] He on whose glory all thy joy should stay,
Is soulless, glory less, and desperate,
