Crying for battle, famine, sword and fire,
Rather then calling for relief or life.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Abdelmunen:] Rubin these rites to Abdelmunen's ghost,
Have pierced by this to Pluto's grave below,
The bells of Pluto ring revenge amain […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Mosbye:] Fie upon women! - This shall be my song.
But bear me hence, for I have lived too long.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Me sees the world is run quite out of square [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Queen Margaret:] […] She bears a duke's revenues on her back […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Messenger:] The wild O'Neill my Lords, is up in arms,
With troops of Irish Kernes that uncontroll'd,
Doth plant themselves within the English pale.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Winchester:] But have you no greater proofs than these?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King Henry:] [...] Her tears will pierce into a marble heart;
The tiger will be mild whiles she doth mourn;
And Nero will be tainted with remorse,
To hear and see her plaints, her brinish tears [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Thou art not false groom son to Baiazet,
He would relent to hear a woman weep,
But thou wast born in desert Caucasus,
And the Hyrcanian tigers gave thee suck.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Duchess:] Welcome is banishment. Welcome were my death.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Eleanor:] Even to my death, for I have lived too long.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Suffolk:] The fox barks not when he would steal the lamb.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Suffolk]: Could curses kill, as doth the mandrake’s groan [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Younger Mortimer:] […] He wears a lord’s revenue on his back […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lancaster:] The wild O'Neill, with swarms of Irish kerns,
Lives uncontroll'd within the English pale.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
"Fondling," she saith, "since I have hemmed thee here
Within the circuit of this ivory pale,
I’ll be a park, and thou shalt be my deer.
Feed where thou wilt, on mountain or in dale;
Graze on my lips, and if those hills be dry,
Stray lower, where the pleasant fountains lie. [...]"

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Younger Mortimer:] But hath your grace no other proof than this?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lavinia:] [...] When did the tiger's young ones teach the dam?
O, do not learn her wrath; she taught it thee;
The milk thou suck'dst from her did turn to marble.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Queen Isabella:] Nay, to my death; for too long have I liv'd […]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [York:] Take her away, for she hath lived too long [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King Edward:] O my stars!
Why do you lour unkindly on a king!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: I warrant we have old hacksters in this great Grandmother of Corporations, Madame Troynovant, that have not backbitten any of their neighbours with the tooth of envy in this twenty year, in the wrinkles of whose face, ye may hide false dice, and play at cherry-pit in the dint of their cheeks, yet these aged mothers of iniquity will have their deformities new plastered over, and wear nosegays of yellow hair on their furies foreheads, when age hath written Hoe God be here, on their bald burnt parchment pates.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Bassianus:] Accompanied but with a barbarous Moor [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Lucius:] Good uncle, take you in this barbarous Moor [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lightborn:] You shall not need to give instructions;
'Tis not the first time I have kill'd a man.
I learn'd in Naples how to poison flowers,
To strangle with a lawn thrust down the throat,
To pierce the wind pipe with a needle's point,
Or, whilst one is asleep, to take a quill,
And blow a little powder in his ears,
Or open his mouth, and pour quick-silver downe.
But yet I have a braver way then these.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [King Edward:] Let Pluto’s bells ring out my fatal knell […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [King Richard:] Can no man tell me of my unthrifty son?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Richard:] A horse, a horse, my kingdom for a horse!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Richard:] Now is the winter of our discontent
Made glorious summer by this sun of York.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Queen Margaret:] So now prosperity begins to mellow
And drop into the rotten mouth of death.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [King Henry:] That blood should sprinkle me to make me grow.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Was never whore of Babylon so betrap with abominations, as his style (like the dog-house in the fields) is pestered with stinking filth. His vainglory (which some take to be his gentlewoman) he hath new painted an inch thick.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [King:] (he makes horns at the Guise) .

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Richard:] [...] I say again, give out
That Anne my queen is sick and like to die.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[...] And pray'd the narrow toiling Hellespont,
To part in twain, that he [Leander] might come and go […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Stone him with hard'ned hearts harder than stones,
An let mild women to him lose their mildness,
Wilder to him than tigers in their wildness.
Let him have time to tear his curléd hair.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Aumerle:] Faith, none for me, except the northeast wind,
Which then blew bitterly against our faces,
Awaked the sleeping rheum and so by chance
Did grace our hollow parting with a tear.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Puck:] I'll put a girdle round about the Earth
In forty minutes.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Sampson:] [...] we will not carry coals.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Juliet:] Gallop apace, you fiery-footed steeds,
Towards Phoebus’ lodging. Such a wagoner
As Phaëton would whip you to the west
And bring in cloudy night immediately.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Mercutio:] [Tybalt is] More than prince of cats.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Chorus:] […] A pair of star-crossed lovers [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Romeo:] O, I am fortune's fool.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [York:] [...] From plume-plucked Richard [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Romeo:] It seems she hangs upon the cheek of night
As a rich jewel in an Ethiop's ear [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: A group pf simple mechanics stage a Greek play for the wedding of Duke Theseus of Athens.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Juliet:] And shrieks like mandrakes torn out of the earth [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Old Stukeley:] When saw you that unthrifty Boy, Tom Stukeley?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: O'Neill

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Shylock:] [...] Why he cannot abide a gaping pig [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [...] and though this fiend be begotten of his father's own blood, yet is he different from his nature, and were he not sure that jealousy could not make him a cuckold, he had long since published him for a bastard; - you shall know him by this, his heart steeled against charity; he walks for the most part in black under colour of gravity and looks as pale as the visard of the ghost which cried so miserably at the Theatre like an oyster wife, Hamlet, revenge.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Holofernes:] The deer was, as you know, sanguis, in blood, ripe as the pomewater, who now hangeth like a jewel in the ear of caelo, the sky [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Prince Henry:] I am the cygnet to this pale faint swan,
Who chants a doleful hymn to his own death [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Pistol:] He woos both high and low, both rich and poor,
Both young and old, one with another, Ford.
He loves the gallimaufry. Ford, perpend.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Prince:] Come, brother John. Full bravely hast thou fleshed
Thy maiden sword.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hotspur:] Revolted Mortimer!
He never did fall off, my sovereign liege,
But by the chance of war.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Falstaff:] [...] Well, 'tis no matter. Honor pricks me on. Yea, but how if honor prick me off when I come on? How then? Can honor set to a leg? No. Or an arm? No. Or take away the grief of a wound? No. Honor hath no skill in surgery, then? No. What is honor? A word. What is in that word "honor"? What is that "honor"? Air. A trim reckoning. Who hath it? He that died o' Wednesday. Doth he feel it? No. Doth he hear it? No. 'Tis insensible, then? Yea, to the dead. But will it not live with the living? No. Why? Detraction will not suffer it. Therefore, I'll none of it. Honor is a mere scutcheon. And so ends my catechism.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Pistol:] Then feed and be fat, my fair Calipolis.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Michael Drayton (quem toties honoris & amoris causa nomino) among scholars, soldiers, Poets, and all sorts of people, is held for a man of virtuous disposition, honest conversation, and well governed carriage, which is almost miraculous among good wits in these declining and corrupt times, when there is nothing but roguery in villainous man, & when cheating and craftiness is counted the clearest wit, and fondest wisdom.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
A man, a man, a kingdom for a man!
Why, how now, currish, mad Athenian?
Thou cynic dog, see'st not streets do swarm
With troops of men?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Benedick:] I will fetch you a toothpicker now from the furthest inch of Asia [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Prince:] Good morrow, masters. Put your torches out.
The wolves have preyed, and look, the gentle day
Before the wheels of Phoebus, round about
Dapples the drowsy east with spots of gray.
Thanks to you all, and leave us. Fare you well.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Puntarvolo:] [...] Here comes one that will carry coals; ergo, will hold my dog [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Boy:] [...] Nym and Bardolph are sworn brothers in filching, and in Calais they stole a fire shovel. I knew by that piece of service the men would carry coals.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Chorus:] Gentles, if ere you have beheld the passions,
The combats of his soul who being a king,
By some usurping hand hath been deposed
From all his royalties: even such a soul,
Such eyes, such heart swollen big with sighs and tears,
The star-crossed sun of Fortunatus wears.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Chorus:][...] Yet sit and see,
Minding true things by what their mock'ries be.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Chorus:] Leashed in like hounds, should famine, sword, and fire
Crouch for employment.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Touchstone:] Most shallow man. Thou worms' meat in respect of a good piece of flesh, indeed. Learn of the wise and perpend: civet is of a baser birth than tar, the very uncleanly flux of a cat. Mend the instance, shepherd.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ghost:] [...] Thus was I, sleeping, by a brother's hand
Of life, of crown, of queen at once dispatched,
Cut off, even in the blossoms of my sin,
Unhouseled, disappointed, unaneled,
No reck'ning made, but sent to my account
With all my imperfections on my head.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King:] [...] O, my offense is rank, it smells to heaven;
It hath the primal eldest curse upon 't,
A brother’s murder.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Balurdo:] [...] I were as he, I would bear no coals, law I, I begin to swell, puff.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Ophelia

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King:] My words fly up, my thoughts remain below;
Words without thoughts never to heaven go.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Polonius:] The best actors in the world, either for tragedy, comedy, history, pastoral, pastoral-comical, historical-pastoral [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...] Now get you to my lady's chamber, and tell her, let her paint an inch thick, to this favor she must come.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: (Enter Piero, unbraced, his arms bare, smeared in blood, a poniard in one hand bloody, and a torch in the other, Strotzo following him with a cord

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] The time is out of joint.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Polonius (aside):] Though this be madness, yet there is method in it.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] I hold it not honesty to have it thus set down, for yourself, sir, should be old as I am, if like a crab you could go backward.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] [...]<span class="quote"> frailty, thy name is woman<span class="quote">!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Philip:] And for this Barbarous Moor, and his black train,
Let all the Moors be banished from Spain.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Polonius:] Take this from this, if this be otherwise.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King:] What if this cursèd hand
Were thicker than itself with brother’s blood?
Is there not rain enough in the sweet heavens
To wash it white as snow?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hamlet:] See what a grace was seated on this brow,
Hyperion’s curls, the front of Jove himself,
An eye like Mars’ to threaten and command,
A station like the herald Mercury
New-lighted on a heaven-kissing hill
A combination and a form indeed
Where every god did seem to set his seal
To give the world assurance of a man.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
For murder, though it have no tongue, will speak
With most miraculous organ.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] (taking the skull) Alas, poor Yorick! I knew him, Horatio—a fellow of infinite jest, of most excellent fancy.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Gravedigger Scene

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hamlet:] I’ll speak to it, though hell itself should gape And bid me hold my peace.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King:] [...] The harlot's cheek beautied with plast'ring art
Is not more ugly to the thing that helps it [...]

[Hamlet:] I have heard of your paintings

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Apollo:] But pray ye Maid, it will be very good,
To take the shade, in this unhaunted wood:
This flowering bay with branches large and great,
Will shroud ye safely, from the parching heat.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Viola:] [...] Alas, our frailty is the cause, not we,
For such as we are made of, such we be.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Camillo:] And of Beauty what tongue would not speak the best: since it is Jewel that hangs upon the brow of heaven, the best collar that can be laid upon the cheek of earth: beauty makes men Gods immortal, by making mortal men to live even in love.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Quadratus:] Ha he mounts Chirall on the wings of fame.
A horse, a horse, my kingdom for a horse,
 Look thee, I speak play scraps.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [2nd theatre boy:] Where art thou, boy? where is Calipolis?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Quadratus:] Feed and be fat my fair Calipolis!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Tucca:] Feed and be fat my fair Calipolis, stir not my beauteous wriggle-tails.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Whilst that my glory midst the clouds was hid,
Like to a Jewel in an Ethiop's ear.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Malevole:] I'll go to pray and come to you.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Malevole:] Great slaves fear better than love, born naturally for a coal-basket [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Claudio:] Thus can the demigod Authority
Make us pay down for our offense, by weight,
The words of heaven: on whom it will, it will;
On whom it will not, so; yet still ’tis just.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Othello:] Excellent wretch! Perdition catch my soul
But I do love thee!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Puts off his clothes; his shirt he only wears,
Much like mad-Hamlet; thus as passion tears.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hipolito]: My Infelices face: her brow, her eye,
The dimple on her cheek: and such sweet skill,
Hath from the cunning workman's pencil flown,
These lips look fresh and lively as her own,
Seeming to move and speak. Las! now I see,
The reason why fond women love to buy
Adulterate complexion: here 'tis read,
False colours last after the true be dead.
Of all the Roses grafted on her cheeks,
Of all the graces dancing in her eyes,
Of all the Music set upon her tongue,
Of all that was past womans excellence,
In her white bosom, look! a painted board,
Circumscribes all: Earth can no bliss afford.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Bussy:] [...] great sea-men, using all their wealth
And skills in Neptunes deep invisible paths,
In tall ships richly built and ribbed with brass,
To put a Girdle round about the world.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Barrisor:] I have heard of a fellow, that by a fixed imagination looking upon a Bulbaiting, had a visible pair of horns grow out of his forehead.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Quintiliano:] And yet take heed you swear by no man's bread but your own, for that may breed a quarrel: above all things you must carry no coals.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Duke:] Admit I had, thou killst her now again;
And art more savage than a barbarous Moor.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: This falling away of them, [...] hastied the last of the once hoped-for Prince, as from him that must notoriously know [...] that his father's Empire and Government, was but as the Poetical Furry in a Stage-action, complete yet with horrid and Woful Tragedies: a first, but no second to any Hamlet; and that now Revenge, just Revenge was coming with his Sword drawn against him, his royal Mother, and dearest Sister, to fill up those Murdering Scenes.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Security:] [...] A boat, a boat, a boat, a full hundred Marks for a boat.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Don Zuccone:] [...] A fool, a fool, a fool! my Coxcombe for a fool!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Touchstone:] Master me no more Son if though think's me worthy to by thy father.
[Gertrude:] Sun? Now good Lord how he shines and you mark him! he's a gentleman.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Caesar:] […] And fearlessly past the toiling Hellespont,
Famous for amorous Leander's death […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Gond.:] My Lord, I speak not this to gain new grace,
But howsoever you esteem my words,
My love and duty will not suffer me
To see you favour such a prostitute,
And I stand by dumb; without Rack, Torture,
Or Strappado, I'll unrip myself,
I do confess I was in company with that pleasing peace of frailty, that we call woman;
I do confess after along and tedious seige, I yielded.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
And might it not, as Lady sometimes joy,
T'have decked, and trim'd this now rainbeaten face,
With many a trick, and new-found pleasing toy?
Which if that now, she did behold her case,
 Although on earth, she were for to remain,
She would not paint, nor trim it up again.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lady Macbeth:] The raven himself is hoarse
That croaks the fatal entrance of Duncan
Under my battlements.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Captain:] Here do I mean to crunch, to munch, to eat,
To feed, and be fat my fine Calipolis.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Some on their heads did bear the fatal sign,
Which of fools future fortune did divine,
Others again Morisko caps did wear
Maid-marrian-like with brooches in each ear
And Indian-like did paint inch thick in view;
Though nature‘s red and white were Angel‘s hue.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Sicinius:] He loved his mother dearly.
[Menenius:] [...] There is no more mercy in him than there is milk in a male tiger.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: The Historie of Hamblet

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Count:] Long mayst thou wear thy Knightshood and thy Spurs
Prick thee to Honour on, and prick off Curs [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Joy at the uprising of this Sun, and Son [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Worldly:] What louring Star rul'd my Nativity [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[D’Amville:] What groan is that?
[…] The cries of mandrakes never touch'd the ear with more sad horror than that voice does mine.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Languebeau:] [...] Verily my Lord, my praise came short of her worth. She excedes a jewel. This is but only for ornament, she both for ornament and use.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Seldom:] [...] Did you never see
The Play, where the fat Knight hight Old-castle,
Did tell you truly what this honor was?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Rogero:] [...] No, but I'll show him better metal than ere the Gallimaufry his father used.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Florizell:] [...] But as th' unthought-on accident is guilty
To what we wildly do, so we profess
Ourselves to be the slaves of chance, and flies
Of every wind that blows.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Hercules:] That the luxurious slave were sensible
Of torture; not th'infernals with more pangs
Could plague the villain than Alcides should.
Ixions bones racked on the torturing wheel
Should be a pastime: the three snake-hair'd sisters,
That lash offenders with their whips of steel,
Should seem to dally, when with every string
They cut the flesh like razors [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Alonso:] I'll seek him deeper than e’er plummet sounded [...].

[Prospero:] And deeper than did ever plummet sound
I'll drown my book.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [2nd Officer:] He could not abide to see a Pig's head gaping [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Wolsey:] He parted frowning from me, as if ruin
Leaped from his eyes. So looks the chafèd lion
Upon the daring huntsman that has galled him,
Then makes him nothing.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ferdinand] [...] He that can compass me, and know my drifts,
May say he hath put a girdle 'bout the world,
And sounded all her quicksands.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Gardener:] Most magnificent and peerless Deity, lo, I, the surveyor of Lady Flora's works, welcome your grace with fragrant phrases into her Bowers, beseeching your greatness to bear with the late wooden entertainment of the Wood-men, for Woods are more full of weeds than wits, but gardens are weeded, and Gardeners witty, as may appear by me. I have flowers for all fancies, thyme for truth, rosemary for remembrance, roses for love, Heart's Ease for joy, and thousands more, which all harmoniously rejoice at your presence [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Ajax:] [...] Love, see this;
And laugh old Grand-sir: Ha, ha, ha, by hell
I'll shake thy Kingdom for't: not look on Ajax?
The triple headed-dog, the whips of Steel,
The ravenous Vulture, and the restless stone
Are all mere fables [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[...] he's gone & with him what A world are dead.
which he revive'd, to be revived so,
no more young Hamlet, old Hieronimo,
kind Lear, the Greyed Moore, and more beside,
that lied in him; have now for ever died,
oft have I seen him, leap into the Grave
smiting the person which he seem'd to have
of A sad Lover with so true an Eye
that there I would have sworn, he meant to die [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
A Scrivener (about nine a clocke at night)
Sat close in's shop, and earnestly did write,
The villany abroad suspecting not,
While two observing him, thus laid a plot,
Quoth one to t'other, snatch thou off his hat:
The which he did, and ran away with that:
The Scrivener in haste his shop forsakes,
And for to overtake him undertakes,
So while he follows him that runs away
The other rascal watching for his pray,
Enters the shop as bold as bold might be,
And takes his cloak and so away goes he.
Scrivener comes back, bare headed as he went,
Missing his cloak was far worse discontent,
Quoth he what case am I brought in to night,
Of hat and cloak being uncased quite?
I will not cry Hamlet Revenge my grieves,
But I will call Hang-man Revenge on thieves.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Somebody disguises himself as a parson to perform a double wedding ceremony so that the resulting marriages will be invalid.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Sampson:] [...] Look up brave friend, I have no means to rescue thee, my Kingdom for a sword.
[Champernell:] I'll sword you presently. I'll claw your skin-coat too.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Harpax:] [...] your son,
The ne'er-enough commended Antoninus,
So well hath fleshed his maiden sword, and died
His snowy plumes so deep in enemies' blood,
That besides public grace, beyond his hopes
There are rewards propounded.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Anabell:] No, loathsome Goat, more, more I am that Goddess,
That here with whips of steel in hell hereafter
Scourge rape and theft [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Cordolente:] O star-crossed Love!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[1st Slave:] Both you and I are seen in the base act,
Slandering spotless honour; an act so base,
The barbarous Moor would blush at.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Don John:] […] their countryman
that put a girdle round about the world […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Albovine:] Hold, Paradine.
Tis my last suit, that thou survive
To minister a just revenge on those
Whom I proscribe, help my quivering limbs,
And seat me in the chair - [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[King:] Throw defiance back down their throats, and of our Heralds
Northumberland the honor shall be thine, tell 'um
We come to scourge their pride with whips of steel,
Their City hath from Justice snatch'd her sword
To strike their Sovereign, who has turned the point
Upon their own breasts, tell 'em this.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hermegild:] You are the King's Jewel, and hang richly in his ear.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Hermegild:] I vow to […] sink myself lower than a Plummet[...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Paradine:] A pale swan hath sung my Dirge! O fatal music!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Paradine:] Oh, oh! these are the Mandrake's groans (fatal!)

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Albovine:] So pale and timorous! I'll sooner couple
With a Mandrake, and beget groans.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Alphonso:] Now I am great,
You are my Queen, and I have wrong'd a merit,
More than my service in the humblest lowness
Can ever recompense. I'll rather wish
To meet whole hosts of dangers, and encounter
The stabled whips of steel, then ever part
From those sweet eyes: not time shall sue divorce
'Twixt me and this great miracle of Nature.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Lucio:] Excellent wretch! I am undone with joy [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Joshua:] [...] Tybert the Cat; as it is in the painted cloth of the Bull, and Cock [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Peter:] Call ye this Honour? a pox of honour [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Bidstand:] Come come ye furies with your whips of steel
And all hell's torments let the monster feel
Guilty of this black crime our angry Power
Lets one his guilty head just vengeance shower
Untie Ixion from the torturing wheel
No longer let tir'd Tythius bosom feel
The greedy vulture's beak, set free from pain
All guilty souls that we may turn the same
Upon this dire offender, who hath killed
My daughter and with grief my bosom filled.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
There, painted Pride lives crowned in flaming fire
The Glorious Strumpet, whipped with burning wire [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Bertoldo:] [...] look on England,
The empress of the European isles,
And unto whom alone ours yields precedence,
When did she flourish so, as when she was
The mistress of the ocean. Her navies
Putting a girdle round about the world [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Besse:] Could my Spencer
Think that a barbarous Moor could be so train'd
In humain virtues?

[Besse:] Prize you my love no better, than to rate it
Beneath the friendship of a barbarous Moor?

[Spencer:] I prize my honour, and a Christian's faith,
Above what earth can yield: shall Fesse report,
Unto our country's shame, and to the scandal
Of our religion, that a barbarous Moor
Can exceed us in nobleness?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Asotus:] Phoebus, whip
Thy lazy team, run headlong to the west,
I long to taste the banquet of the night.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
If swoll'n with poison, he lay in his last bed
His body with a sere-bark covered,
Drawing his breath, as thick and short, as can
The nimblest crocheting musician [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Aphelia

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [Clotair:] Set down, set down your honourable load.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Prospero:] [...] so Ravens croak
When they fly over the mansions of the sick
And bode their deaths.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Evandra:] Who is it that assumes the office of
The dying Swan?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Spirit:] "[...] The water Nymphs that in the bottom plaid,
Held up their pearled wrists and took her in,
Bearing her straight to aged Nereus Hall,
Who piteous of her woes, rear'd her lank head,
And gave her to his daughters to imbathe
In nectar'd lavers strew'd with Asphodil,
And through the porch and inlet of each sense
Dropt in Ambrosial Oils till she reviv'd,
And underwent a quick immortal change
Made Goddess of the River [...]."

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Lepida:] [...] Why then employ your burning whips of steel,
Lash with eternal lashes, there, there, there,
Excellent Furies how you do excel,
So, so, so, so, tis holy day in hell.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: We must do to others, not as honor pricks us on.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Orsa:] The slave of chance
One of Fortune's fools;
A thing she kept alive on earth
To make her sport.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Pellegrin:] We're in excellent humour,
Let's have another bottle,
And give out the Anne my wife is dead,
Shall I Gentlemen?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Rampino:] [...] they're Mandrakes' groans and still
Bode death [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: A trout hamlet with four legs. Soterichi lecti.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Orco:] [...] till thou fall'd lower
Than a plummet, that is threescore years a-sinking.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: As swift as thought.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Desperate torments must have desperate cures.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Suspicion always haunts the guilty mind.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Discretion is the better part of valour.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Uneasy lies the head, that wears a Crown.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Thieves are Diana's Foresters or Gentlemen of the Shade.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: No beast so fierce but knows some touch of pity.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: That wrens may prey where eagles dare not perch.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: O Tiger's heart wrapped in a woman's hide.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Better than he have yet worn Vulcan's badge.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Even such kin as the parish heiress are to the town-bull.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Did ever Raven sing so like a Lark?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: The Raven doth not hatch a Lark.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Thanks, the exchequer of the Poor.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
What do'st thou mean to stand behind the noon
And pluck bright honor from the pale fac'd moon?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [...] the frighted judgment of his brain (that then was ray'd with his own hair, standing stiffe an end, like ported feathers of some Porcupine).

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: You would have thought Amandus had been trans-elemented (had you beheld him at that instant) but at length, recollecting himself a little, he answered in a distracted tone. But dares Clodomer report this, and not feare a Thunder-bolt (with sawcy Salmoneus ) should pound him (as Anacharsis once in a morter) to peices? You are my King (Sir) I know you beare Divinitie about you, which is your protection, else by the wronged innocence of that abused Lady, were you ingirt with circular flames, and managed oakes, with as much facility as children wield bulrushes, the hilts of this sword should kiss your heart.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: The excellent VIRGINIA will pardon me, if for dilucidation of an argument, I make her pure and unexhausted brows descend to wear a Garland of fertility equal to that laborious and overteeming Mother, the French Kingdom [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: 5. The Reproaches of their Enemies do fully testify this, who cast it still in their Teeth, that they were ignorant and unlearned Men. And indeed that was the great rub that their Doctrine found in the World; it was to the Jews a stumbling Block, and to the Greeks Foolishness; and therefore it appeared to be the Power of God, and not of Man [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: The which the Captain espying, began most debonairly to comfort her dispairful courage, adding moreover with the industrious art of his fluent tongue, that no disgrace or malefaction should be administered her, but such chaste kindness and modest courtesy as should every way correspond with the title of honour.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: I thought (when I saw him first (active as lightning) get up upon his flying Horse) he had been able to have plucked bright Honour from the pale-fac'd Moon [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Now the gathering together of many men, who deliberate of what is to be done or not to be done for the common good of all men, is that which I call a council.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: He was afflicted so that he gave all up to dispair, and thought on nothing, but to finde out a way to undeceive the people, and recover the Lady her honor, and restore his own reputation. Being thus agitated in a Sea of trouble, he continued his accustomed walk through Cleria's street, to shew that he had not yeilded to Diego.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: The Holy Spirit is too pure and gentle a thing to dwell in a mind muddied and disturbed by those impure dregs.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: That ye may, like the Bee, suck Honey out of every Flower; that ye may shine in a Sea of Troubles, as the Pearl shines in the Skie, though it grows in the Sea [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: This perpetual peevishnesse and jealousie, under the alternate Empire of the Prince and of the People, is obnoxious unto every Spark. Nor shall any man shew a reason that will be holding in prudence, why the people of Oceana have blown up their King, but that their Kings did not first blow up them: The rest is discourse for Ladies. Wherefore your Parliaments are not henceforth to come, out of the bag of Æolus , but by the Gallaxy's , to be the perpetual food of the fire of Vesta .

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Of Chastity, Continence
Sister, keep in the rear of your affection,
Out of the shot and danger of desire.
The chariest Maid is prodigall enough,
If she unmask her beauty to the Moon:
Virtue it selfe scapes not calumnious strokes,
The Canker galls the Infants of the Spring
Too oft before their Buttons be disclos’d,
And in the morn and liquid dew of youth,
Contagious blastments are most imminent.
Be wary then; best safety lies in feare:
Youth to it selfe rebels, though none else neer.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
How absolute the knave is! we must speak by the card,
Or else Aequivocation will undo us.
These three years I have taken a note of it;
The age is grown so picked that the Toe
Of the Peasant comes so neer the heel of the Courtier,
He galls his kibe.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
That monster Custom, that all sence doth eat,
Of habits Devil, is Angel yet in this,
That to the use of Actions fair and good
He likewise gives a Frock or Livery,
That aptly is put on.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Our indiscretion sometimes serves us well,
When our deep plots do paul, and that should teach us
There's a divinity that shapes our ends,
Rough hew them how we will.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
We are oft to blame in this,
'Tis too much prov'd, that with devotions visage,
And pious action we doe sugar ore
The Devil himself.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Margaretta:] Thou art still old Truepenny.
[Rinaldo:] Still still, and ever shall be, if I shall, let me strike the stroak, I shall not do thee much harme [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
To whom the valiant Captaine made reply
By one well versed in that Bastard-Tongue :
Illustrious Lord, I shall to thee descry
My Self, my Faith, and th' Armes I bring along.
Neither of Turkish-blood nor breed, am I;
Nor of a Countrey that delights in wrong.
In fair and warlike Europe was I born,
I seek the famous Kingdoms of the Morn.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Embrace.
The female Ivy so
Enrings the barky fingers of the Elm;
And locks her so in his embraces,
As if he meant to pin her to his heart:
Hangs on him
As if increase of appetite did grow
From what it grew on. Cleaving like burrs.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Fear, Fearful.
The bedded hair, like life in excrements,
Start up, and stand on [sic] end.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Fear, Fearful
Distill'd almost to jelly,
harrows the soul, and makes the eyes start from their spheres.
The hair stands an [sic] end
Like quilles upon the fretful porcupine.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Rightly to be great
Is not to stir without great argument,
But greatly to find quarrel in a straw
When honour's at the stake.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
In the most high and palmy state of Rome,
A little ere the mightiest Julius fell,
The Graves stood Tenantless and the sheeted dead
Did squeak and gibber in the Roman streetes:
As Stars with traines of fire and dewes of blood,
Disasters in the Sun, and the moist star
Upon whose influence Neptune's empire stands
Was sick almost to Doomesday with eclipse.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: What to ourselves in passion we propose, – 3, 2, 199: The passion ending, doth the purpose lose. – 3, 2, 200: The violence of either grief or joy – 3, 2, 201: Their own enactures with themselves destroy: – 3, 2, 202: Where joy most revels, grief doth most lament; – 3, 2, 203: Grief joys, joy grieves, on slender accident. – 3, 2, 204: This world is not for aye, nor 'tis not strange – 3, 2, 205: That even our loves should with our fortunes change; – 3, 2, 206: For 'tis a question left us yet to prove, – 3, 2, 207: Whether love lead fortune, or else fortune love.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
To climb steep hills,
Requires slow pace at first, anger is like
A full hot horse, who being allow'd his way
Self-Mettal tyres him.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: In the corrupted currents of this world – 3, 3, 61: Offence's gilded hand may shove by justice, – 3, 3, 62: And oft 'tis seen the wicked prize itself – 3, 3, 63: Buys out the law: but 'tis not so above; – 3, 3, 64: There is no shuffling, there the action lies – 3, 3, 66: Even to the teeth and forehead of our faults, – 3, 3, 67: To give in evidence. What then? what rests?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: And meant to wreck thee; but, beshrew my jealousy! – 2, 1, 125: By heaven, it is as proper to our age – 2, 1, 126: To cast beyond ourselves in our opinions – 2, 1, 127: As it is common for the younger sort – 2, 1, 128: To lack discretion. Come, go we to the king:

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
The great man down, his Favorite flyes,
The poor advanc'd, makes friends of enemies;
And hitherto doth love on fortune tend,
And who not needs shall never want a friend;
And who in want a hollow friend doth try,
Directly seasons him his enemy.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Men counsaile, and speak comfort to that griefe / Which they themselves not feel; but tasting it, / Their counsaile turns to passion, which before / Would give preceptiall medicine to rage, / Fetter strong madnesse in a silken thread, / Charm Ache with Air, and Agony with words. -

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
We're ill by these Grammarians us'd;
We are abus'd by Words, grosly abus'd;
From the Maternal Tomb,
To the Graves fruitful Womb,
We call here Life; but Life's a name
That nothing here can truly claim:
This wretched Inn, where we scarce stay to bait:
We call our Dwelling-place;
We call one Step a Race:
But Angels in their full enlightned state,
Angels who Live, and know what 'tis to Be,
Who all the nonsense of our Language see,
Who speak Things, and our Words, their ill-drawn Pictures scorn,
When we by a foolish Figure say,
Behold an old man Dead! then they
Speak properly, and cry, Behold a man-child born.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Oh Life, thou Nothings younger Brother!
So like, that one might take One for the other!
What's Some Body, or No Body?
In all the Cobwebs of the Schoolmens trade,
We no such nice Distinction woven see,
As 'tis To be, or Not to Be.
Dream of a Shadow! a Reflection made
From the false glories of the gay reflected Bow [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
The Silver Moon with terrour paler grew,
And neighbring Hermon sweated slowly dew;
Swift Jordan started, and straight backward fled,
Hiding among thick reeds his aged head [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
I would sin oft, and on my guilty brow
Wear every misperfection that I ow
Open and visible [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Think of those (b) Worthies that sayled through such a Sea of troubles for Christ, not accepting deliverance. Think of those blessed Martyrs, that Sung in prison, embraced the fagots, kissed the stake, and triumphantly clapt their hands in the midst of devouring flames.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: A holy Silence will give a man such a quiet possession of his own soul, that all the storms of afflictions shall not move him, it will make him stand like a Rock in a Sea of Troubles [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: 3. Let death come when it will, it can do you no harm; for it will be but only a passage out of a prison - into a palace; out of a sea of troubles - into a haven of rest; out of a crowd of enemies - into an innumerable company of true, loving, and faithful friends; out of shame, reproach, and contempt - into exceeding great and eternal glory!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Why am I mockt with death, and length'nd out
To deathless pain? how gladly would I meet
Mortalitie my sentence, and be Earth
Insensible, how glad would lay me down
As in my Mothers lap! there I should rest
And sleep secure; his dreadful voice no more
Would Thunder in my ears, no fear of worse
To mee and to my ofspring would torment me
With cruel expectation. Yet one doubt
Pursues me still, least all I cannot die,
Least that pure breath of Life, the Spirit of Man
Which God inspir'd, cannot together perish
With this corporeal Clod; then in the Grave,
Or in some other dismal place, who knows
But I shall die a living Death?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
These are to let you understand and know,
That love will creepe there where it cannot go.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Now she steeps
Her down in tears, a floud of sorrow weeps
Of power (if penitent) to expiate
Youths vigorous sins, but all her mourning sate
Beneath a darker Vayle then that which shades
Repentant grief, since sinne but wisht invades
The soul with that which leads to horror, when
Grief for sins past bring into light agen
One through a sea of trouble leads the way
To a safe Harbour, th'other casts away
Poor ship-wrackt Mortals, when by deaths swift stroak
Lifes feeble hold is from hopes anchor broke.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: The Players have a Play, where they bring in a Tinker, and make him believe himself a Lord, and when they have satisfied their humour, they made him a plain Tinker again; Gentlemen, but that this was a great while ago, I should have thought this Play had been made of me; for if ever two cases were alike, 'tis the Tinker's and mine.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
The Grave-Makers.
ARGUMENT. While, he is making the Grave, for a Lady that drown'd her selfe, Hamlet and his friend interrupt him with several Questions. ACTORS NAMES. Grave-maker, and his Man, Hamlet, and his Friend.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Welcome bright Starre, the prodrome of the day,
With whom the Sun of glory shall display
His golden banners, and restore the Light
Of truth eclipst by an erroneous night:
He liv'd in exile long, and Flanders then
Was th' Eagles neast, or the true Lions den:
He past a Sea of troubles; and each wave
Of grief he flatted with a soul more brave.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
But thou must put me to the purchase
Of such a pipe, which used in Churches,
Hath brought to pulpit, Roger Korum,
(As Bumpkin swears) who long before um
Knew not (Jack Falstaff-wise) since ever born
Church inside more, than does a peppercorn.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: But that since it was a dream and that I took so much real pleasure in it, what a happy thing it would be, if when we are in our graves (as Shakespeere resembles it), we could dream, and dream but such dreams as this - that then we should not need to be so fearful of death as we are this plaguetime.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: I withdrew as soon as I had delivered my Paper, giving her leave to read in private, what my Love had dictated. About a quarter of an hour after she called me to her, assuring me in a day or two, I should receive an answer to the purpose; and so absconding her displeasure, she sent me with all expedition home again.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
As when the Sun new ris'n
Looks through the Horizontal misty Air,
Shorn of his Beams; or from behind the Moon
In dim Eclips disastrous twilight sheds
On half the Nations, and with fear of change
Perplexes Monarchs.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
So saying, her rash hand in evil hour
Forth reaching to the Fruit, she pluckd, she eat:
Earth felt the wound, and Nature from her seat
Sighing through all her Works gave signs of woe,
That all was lost.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Satan:] "[...] Thou wouldst thy self, no doubt,
And boldly venture to whatever place
Fardest from pain, where thou mightst hope to change
Torment with ease, and soonest recompence
Dole with delight, which in this place I sought;
To thee no reason; who knowst onely good,
But evil hast not tri'd: [...]"

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
So spake the Enemie of Mankind, enclos'd
In Serpent, Inmate bad, and toward Eve
Addressd his way, not with indented wave,
Prone on the ground, as since, but on his reare,
Circular base of rising foulds, that tour'd
Fould above fould a surging Maze, his Head
Crested aloft, and Carbuncle his Eyes;
With burnisht Neck of verdant Gold, erect
Amidst his circling Spires, that on the grass
Floted redundant: [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Michael:] "[...] His Cattel must of Rot and Murren die,
Botches and blaines must all his flesh imboss,
And all his people; Thunder mixt with Haile,
Haile mixt with fire must rend th' Egyptian Skie
And wheel on th' Earth, devouring where it rouls;
What it devours not, Herb, or Fruit, or Graine,
A darksom Cloud of Locusts swarming down
Must eat, and on the ground leave nothing green: [...]."

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
To Heav'n their prayers
Flew up, nor missed the way, by envious windes
Blow'n vagabond or frustrate: in they passd
Dimentionless through Heav'nly dores [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Moloch:] "[...] [W]hat can be worse
Then to dwell here, driv'n out from bliss, condemn'd
In this abhorred Deep to utter woe;
Where pain of unextinguishable fire
Must exercise us without hope of end
The Vassals of his anger, when the Scourge
Inexorably, and the torturing hour
Calls us to Penance? [...]"

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Yet soon he heald; Spirits that live throughout
Vital in every part, not as frail Man
In Entrailes, Heart or Head, Liver or Reines,
Cannot but by annihilating die;
Nor in thir liquid texture mortal wound
Receive, no more then can the fluid Aire: [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Which when Bëëlzebub perceiv'd, then whom,
Satan except, none higher sat, with grave
Aspect he rose, and in his rising seemd
A Pillar of State; deep on his Front engraven
Deliberation sat and publick care;
And Princely counsel in his face yet shon,
Majestick though in ruin: [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[T]hese were from without
The growing miseries, which Adam saw
Alreadie in part, though hid in gloomiest shade,
To sorrow abandond, but worse felt within,
And in a troubl'd Sea of passion tost,
Thus to disburden sought with sad complaint.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Belial:] "[...] [W]hile wee perhaps
Designing or exhorting glorious Warr,
Caught in a fierie Tempest, shall be hurld
Each on his rock transfixt, the sport and prey
Or racking whirlwinds, or for ever sunk
Under yon boiling Ocean, wrapt in Chains;
There to converse with everlasting groans,
Unrespited, unpitied, unrepreevd,
Ages of hopeless end; this would be worse. [...]"

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Adam:] "[...] But say
That Death be not one stroke, as I suppos'd,
Bereaving sense, but endless misery
From this day onward, which I feel begun
Both in me, and without me, and so last
To perpetuitie; Ay me, that fear
Comes thundring back with dreadful revolution
On my defensless head; both Death and I
Am found Eternal, and incorporate both,
Nor I on my part single, in me all
Posteritie stands curst[.] [...]"

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: As varnish on a harlot's cheek [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: [...] with curious eye perus'd him [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Son of God:] "[...] Should I of these the liberty regard,
Who freed, as to thir ancient Patrimony,
Unhumbl'd, unrepentant, unreformd,
Headlong would follow; and to thir Gods perhaps
Of Bethel and of Dan? no, let them serve
Thir enemies, who serve Idols with God. [...]"

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Son of God:] "[...] I can at will, doubt not, as soon as thou,
Command a Table in this Wilderness,
And call swift flights of Angels ministrant
Arrayd in Glory on my cup to attend:
Why shouldst thou then obtrude this diligence,
In vain, where no acceptance it can find? [...]"

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Harapha:] "Thou durst not thus disparage glorious arms
Which greatest Heroes have in battel worn,
Thir ornament and safety, had not spells
And black enchantments, some Magicians Art
Armd thee or charmed thee strong, which thou from Heaven
Feigndst at thy birth was giv'n thee in thy hair,
Where strength can least abide, though all thy hairs
Were bristles rang'd like those that ridge the back
Of chaf'd wild Boars, or ruffl'd Porcupines."

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
[Dalila:] "[...] To what I did thou shewdst me first the way.
But I to enemies revealed, and should not.
Nor shouldst thou have trusted that to womans frailty:
Ere I to thee, thou to thyself wast cruel. [...]"

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
The Master, the Swabber, the Boatswain, and I,
The Gunner and his Mate

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Where the Bee sucks, there suck I,
In a Cowslips Bell I lie

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Who is Silvia? What is she?
That all our Swains commend her etc.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
You spotted Snakes with double tongue,
Thorny Hedge-hogs be not seen etc.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Tell me, where is Fancy bred,
Or in the heart, or in the dead? etc.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
You that chuse not by the view,
Chance as fair, and chuse as true; etc.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Under the Green-wood tree,
Who loves to lie with me, etc.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
What shall he have that kill'd the Deer
His Leathern skin and Horns to wear; etc.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Wedding is great Juno's Crown,
O blessed Bond of Board and Bed; etc.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
When Daisies pied, and Violets blue,
And Cuckoo-buds of yellow hue, etc.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
When Icicles hang by the wall,
And Dick the shepherd blows his nail, etc.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Take, oh take those Lips away,
That so sweetly were forsworn etc.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Sigh no more Ladies, sigh no more,
Men were deceivers ever, etc.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Lawn as white as driven Snow,
Cypress as black as e're was Crow etc.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Fear no more the heat o'th' Sun,
Nor the furious Winter's rages, etc.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: For if the Good and the Evil be equal-balanced, it must needs be indifferent to that man either to be or not to be, there being not the least Grain of good to determine his Choice: So that he can no more be said to be happy in that Condition, than he could before he was born. And much less, if the Evil exceeds the Good [...]. And when 'tis once come to this (whatever some Mens Metaphysics may perswade them) I am very well satisfied, that 'tis better not to be than to be.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text:
Man! our great business and our aim,
For whom we spread our fruitless snares,
No sooner kindles the designing flame,
But to the next bright object bears
The Trophies of his conquest and our shame:
Inconstancy's the good supream
The rest is airy Notion, empty Dream!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage label
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:text: Vincantio, the Duke of Vienna, announces that he will go away for a diplomatic mission but instead spies on the people disguised as a friar.
